ROASTED GARLIC 🧄🧄🧄🧄🧄🧄🧄

For the best mashed potatoes in all the land…or garlic bread or pasta or salad dressing…options are endless folks 🤤

Slice the tops off. Drizzle with olive oil and let it seep down in the crevices between the cloves. Season with salt and pepper. Wrap in a small piece of foil and bake at 375 for 1 hour until golden brown and fragrant. Let them cool and then squeeeeeze out the garlic.

WHO’S GONNA MAKE IT?! 🤩

Homemade or that jelly stuff from the can???

Tis the question of the evening.

For me, it’s gotta be homemade. I’ve never liked the canned kind.

Homemade cranberry sauce is so easy too!

1lb cranberries, rinsed
1/2 cup water
1/2 cup 100% orange juice
3/4 cup sugar (I used a combo of white and brown)
2 cinnamon sticks
Zest of an orange

Combine the cranberries, water, orange juice and sugar and stir. Cook over medium heat until the cranberries begin to break down, about 5 minutes. Add the cinnamon sticks and cook another 10 minutes until the sauce is thickened. Turn off the heat and add the orange zest. Serve or store until the feast! Lasts up to 5-6 days.

YUM.

HOW TO SPATCHCOCK A TURKEY!!

Quicker cook time
More evenly cooked
Moist, flavorful breast meat
More crispy skin

THIS is the way!

Plus a dry brine to lock in the moisture and flavor 💯

Dry brine:
1/2 cup kosher salt
2 tablespoons brown sugar
Zest of an orange
Ground together:
1 tablespoon peppercorns
2 sprigs fresh rosemary
4 sprigs fresh thyme
1 teaspoon anise seed

To spatchcock, use good quality poultry shears to remove the turkey backbone. Score the breast bone with your knife, flip the turkey over and press down on the breast til it gives and you hear a crack. That’s it! Place in a roasting pan, rub the brine all over, and let sit in the fridge, uncovered until you’re ready to roast! When you’re ready to roast, you’ll rinse off the brine and then brush with oil or butter and cook on top of garlic, carrots, onions, celery and lemons. I usually do 30 minutes at 450, then reduce heat to 350 for another 50-60 minutes and then it’s DONE. Absolute perfect turkey every time.

Happy holidays friends!!

HOMEMADE STOCK!!

Trust me when I say that the flavor of your own broth is a quadrillion times better than storebought and will make your gravy and stuffing/dressing come to life! 🤩

Simply drizzle oil on your turkey backbone, neck and giblets along with carrots, celery, onions, garlic, ginger, thyme sprigs. Season with a little salt and pepper and roast at 450 for 30 minutes until deep golden brown. Scoop everything into a stockpot and add thyme sprigs, peppercorns, bay leaves and a teaspoon of kosher salt. Fill stockpot with water and simmer for several hours until reduced by a third. Strain into mason jars and use immediately or store in fridge for the fridge for 3 weeks or freezer for up to 3 months!

Enjoy! 🤩🦃

🚨LAST MINUTE APPETIZER IDEA🚨

I want to eat this every single day, no joke.

Apples + nuts + brie?!

That is a combo that just really can’t be rivaled.

Plus it’s made with my favorite crunchy, toasted, ever so slightly sweetened @eatsantenuts walnuts.

Here’s how to make:

1 bag @eatsantenuts candied walnuts, roughly chopped
1 round brie (I get the kind from Costco!)
1/4 cup pure maple syrup
Apples, pears, crackers

Slice off the top most piece of rind from the Brie. Place on a lined baking tray and bake at 350 for 5-7 minutes until the inside is nice and melty.

In a small sauté pan over medium heat, toast the walnuts a bit and add the maple syrup. Reduce heat to low and keep it warm.

Remove brie from oven, transfer to a serving tray, which might be slightly difficult considering how melty it is but just go with it, drizzle with maple and nuts and arrange pears, apples and crackers all around.

Dunk to your heart’s delight, be careful, it’s difficult to stop. 🤤

Don’t forget to use code FLAVORFULLIFE for 15% off your entire purchase of @eatsantenuts! (Link in my bio for their website) They are the perfect touch to your holiday cooking plus a great gift idea as well!

Is anyone else feeling the “Monday after Thanksgiving blues!?”

My gosh, it’s brutal! I have like zero motivation to cook, clean, exercise like I normally do.

Enter: super easy weeknight meals like this one.

Hot honey salmon, rice, cucumbers! Dinner done in 20 minutes flat.

There is something about spicy honey that goes so perfectly with salmon. It’s sweet savory perfection.

The marinade/sauce is SO easy:
1/3 cup honey
2 tablespoons butter
1 tablespoon stone ground mustard
1 tablespoon sriracha

Melt together the butter and honey for about 30 seconds in the microwave. Whisk in the mustard and sriracha.

Everything else:
-1lb salmon filet
-garlic powder, salt, pepper, smoked paprika
-cucumbers
-1 tablespoon rice vinegar
-pinch salt and sugar
-1/2 teaspoon toasted sesame oil
-green onions
-steamed jasmine rice

Pat dry a 1lb salmon filet. I buy the wild caught Pacific alaskan salmon from costco. Season with salt, pepper, garlic powder and smoked paprika, measure with your heart! Drizzle half the sauce on the salmon and brush until even coated. Bake at 425 for 12 minutes or under salmon is juuuust flaky and cooked through. If you have a thicker filet, you may need to cook longer.

Thinly slice the cucumbers and toss with rice vinegar, a tiny pinch each of salt and sugar and a touch of toasted sesame oil.

Serve everything up: steamed rice or grain of choice, hot honey salmon, marinated cucumbers, green onions and extra SAUCE.

It’s so simple and so good. I hope y’all give this one a try.

Another SOS meal for the win!! Instant pot pasta and chicken meatballs with lemon herb ricotta.

So quick, easy and balanced!

This recipe is from @pinchofyum! (If you don’t follow their blog you should!)

1–2 tablespoons olive oil 
1lb frozen chicken meatballs (I use the organic ones from Costco!)
one 32-ounce jar of your favorite tomato pasta sauce
1 cup water
10oz small pasta (right here I’m using the organic gemelli from Costco)
salt and pepper to taste

herb lemon ricotta 
1 pound fresh ricotta – mascarpone is a bit more creamy / melty and also delicious!
juice of 1 lemon + a little bit of zest
1 garlic clove, finely grated
2 tablespoons olive oil
1 cup finely chopped mixed chives, parsley, basil
salt and pepper to taste

Place meatballs in the Instant Pot; drizzle with olive oil. Sauté for a couple minutes to get the meatballs a bit browned on the outside – they don’t need to be fully thawed.
Add in this order: pasta, sauce, water. Do not stir. Cook on high pressure for 3 minutes. 
Release steam right away (so your pasta doesn’t overcook and get mushy). Stir to incorporate. A small amount of sticking is normal, but with a few gentle stirs it will lift up and come together perfectly. It will be saucy at first; if you let it rest a few minutes, the sauce will absorb into the pasta and it’ll get a little less saucy.

Mix your herbed ricotta ingredients together while the pasta cooks.

For the asparagus: I like to blanch- boil for 2 minutes and then immediately plunge into an ice bath to stop cooking. Warm with a little olive oil and balsamic glaze and season with salt and pepper.

Serve the hot pasta in bowls with dollops of the ricotta over the top and lots of asparagus!

Let’s talk KNIVES!

Definitely one of the most frequently asked questions- WHAT KNIFE ARE YOU USING!?

So I’m here to spill the deets.

The four knives I use most frequently are a chef knife, paring knife, bread knife and tomato knife.

Chef’s knife: the ultimate multi-purpose blade, this is the knife you should be using for pretty much anything and everything. If you can only have ONE knife, this is the one to go for and the one I’d recommend spending a little extra money on.

Paring knife: perfect for peeling or more intricate knife work (think strawberry roses and kiwi stars!), you’ll want a paring knife. Although I don’t use it as often as my chef’s knife, it definitely has its value.

Bread knife: you all know I love avocado toast. I like to buy a great quality loaf of sourdough from the bakery and slice it myself- so that each day I have a fresh, not-dried-out, delicious piece of bread. I also use my bread knife to slice cheese!

Tomato knife: this one has a serrated edge like a bread but a lot finer. It’s perfect for slicing tomatoes, citrus, stone fruits, anything with a delicate peel!

I have and LOVE a Wusthof block set. I invested in this set years ago and am still loving it today. It has most definitely been worth the investment.

And you definitely want to make sure you are taking good care of your knives! Keep them in a designated safe spot like a magnetic knife rack or knife block. Don’t leave them in the sink or dishwasher! Not only does that slowly ruin them but it’s a definite risk for accidentally cutting yourself.

I made a page on my storefront highlighting everything in this post from knives to sharpener to knife storage and protection. I linked the exact knives I have (Wusthof brand, not sponsored I just really like them) but I also did quite a lot of research and reading to find comparable alternatives that are slightly more cost-effective just in case you are in need of a good quality, but less expensive option.

Chopping is an essential part of healthy eating so a good knife is a MUST!

Gimme the tacos and lay on the Brussels sprouts THICC.

These were absolutely delicious. Plant-based, full of fiber and nutritious veggies. 🤤💯

I had a bunch of uncooked shredded brussels sprouts leftover from Thanksgiving and while meal planning I was pondering how to use them up and BOOM, I remembered these brussels sprouts tacos.

Recipe inspired by @pinchofyum!

For the sauce, in a food processor combine:
-1/4 cup roasted cashews
-2 large cloves garlic
-big pinch of kosher salt
blitz it together, then add:
-1/2 bunch fresh parsley
-1/2 bunch fresh cilantro
-1/4 cup water
-juice of a lime
-2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
-fresh cracked pepper
-1 teaspoon hot honey
process again until smooth and creamy. YUM.

heat a little oil in a cast iron skillet over medium high heat. sauté some peppers, onions and a bag of frozen corn. leave it untouched for a few moments so it gets charred and smoky.

sauté very thinly shaved Brussels sprouts in a little olive oil and season with 1-2 tablespoons taco seasoning.

for serving: smashed avocado, green onions, black beans, lime slices, pickled red onions

In whatever type of warmed tortilla you like pile in the avocado, brussels sprouts, corn pepper mix, black beans, pickled red onions, green onions, creamy cilantro sauce and a big squeeze of lime.

Cry some happy taco tears because these are AMAZE! 🌮🌮🌮🌮🌮

I love granola.

And homemade is where. it’s. at. So simple, wholesome and absolutely delicious. Whole grains, nuts and seeds, a touch of sweetness, heart healthy fats, this recipe is a nutritious WIN!

This recipe is on my blog flavorfulife.com which I’ve linked in my bio!

Ingredients:
4 cups rolled oats*
1 2/3 cups total nuts (I use 1/3 cup each almonds, pistachios, walnuts, pecans and hazelnuts*)
2 tablespoons ground flaxseed
2 tablespoons hemp hearts
1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon
1 teaspoon sea salt
1/2 cup virgin coconut oil
1/2 cup honey or pure maple syrup
1 teaspoon pure vanilla extract
Optional add-ins: 1/2 cup toasted coconut flakes, 1/2 cup dried fruit like cranberries, cherries, raisins, 1/2 cup mini or regular chocolate chips
*the reason I added the hazelnuts at the end was because they were already roasted and I did not want them to burn
*I also added 3 tablespoons brewer’s yeast simply because I have it, it may support lactation (lactating mama here!) and because it’s a fabulous source of valuable B vitamins
*i used @kodiakcakes protein oats to give this granola an extra protein punch!

Instructions
Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
In a large bowl combine oats, nuts, seeds, cinnamon and salt. Stir to combine.
Melt the coconut oil. Whisk in the honey or maple syrup and vanilla. Pour over oat/nut mixture. Stir well to combine and make sure all oats/nuts are moistened. Spread mixture on a silpat or parchment lined baking tray. Bake for 11 minutes. Remove and stir. Return to oven for another 10-11 minutes until oats are toasty golden and nuts are fragrant.
Remove from oven and add in mix-ins if desired. I LOVE adding toasted coconut flakes. The key if you like clumps of granola is to really press the mixture down in a compact, even layer before baking and allow to cool without stirring. Ideally, allow to cool without stirring for at least 30 minutes. The granola will continue to crisp up as it cools.
Store in an airtight container for up to 2-3 weeks or sealed in a gallon-sized Ziploc bag in the freezer for 3-4 months.
Enjoy with milk, yogurt, fruit or just straight up!

It’s official. I’m on a bread bender.

I WILL be making this 4 ingredient loaf every week for the foreseeable future.

It’s soooo easy, flour, yeast, salt and water….are ya kidding me? And it makes an absolutely incredible loaf of fresh baked bread.

I prep this after the girls go to bed the evening before I know we will need it, let it proof for a good 18 hours or so and then plop it in the oven at dinner time and BOOM. Bread magic.

I posted this a couple weeks ago but here’s the recipe again in case ya missed it.

3 cups flour
1/2 teaspoon active dry yeast
1 1/2 teaspoon salt
1 1/2 cups room temp water

Stir together the flour, yeast and salt. Add the water and stir until a dough ball forms, it’ll look kinda scrappy and weird. Cover with plastic wrap and a clean kitchen towel and let it sit at room temp for 12-18 hours. I made mine at about 11pm and it was perfect for dinner the next day! Store in a draft free area.

Remove, shape into a dough ball. Preheat oven to 450 and place a 6 quart Dutch oven in the oven to preheat. When oven is preheated place dough on a piece of parchment paper and put it in the Dutch oven. Cover and cook for 30 minutes, remove the lid and cook an additional 10-15 minutes until browned and beautiful.

You will need a Dutch oven or an oven safe pot with a tight fitting lid to make this recipe. If you do not have a Dutch oven though, may I HIGHLY recommend you ask for one for Christmas, it is my absolute number one favorite pot/pan in my kitchen!

(linked in my storefront under pots and pans if you want a link!)

Well last time I made this super easy 4 ingredient loaf of homemade bread I paired it with broccoli cheddar soup…so this time i decided to really live on the edge and make cauliflower cheese soup 🤘🏼🤘🏼

And omg, somehow it was even better than the broccoli cheddar. So simple. So cheesy. So freaking bomb.com.

I kinda combined a few of my fave recipes online and here’s what I did:

-1 large head cauliflower, cut into florets (I prep and wash my veggies at the beginning of the week so it’s super easy day of!)
-1 tablespoon extra virgin olive oil
- 1 teaspoon smoked paprika
-kosher salt and black pepper
-2 tablespoons fresh oregano leaves
-3 tablespoons salted butter
-3 tablespoons all-purpose flour (or all-purpose GF flour)
-1/2 teaspoon chipotle chili powder
-1/2 teaspoon onion powder
-1 1/2 cups whole milk
-3 cups veggie or chicken broth (preferably homemade, I used my homemade turkey bone broth! that’s why it’s slightly gelatinous)
-1-2 cups shredded sharp cheddar cheese
 
Instructions
Preheat oven to 425 degrees F. On a baking sheet, toss the cauliflower, olive oil, paprika, and a pinch each of salt and pepper. Roast for 25 minutes until tender and crispy.

Meanwhile, make the soup base. Melt the butter in a dutch oven over medium heat. Whisk in the flour, chipotle chili powder, onion powder and oregano. Cook 1 minute. Slowly add the milk, whisking until combined. Season with salt and pepper. Add the broth/stock. Bring to a low boil. Stir in the cheeses. Add the cauliflower and toss. Cook another 3-5 minutes.

I loooove a good meatless Monday meal, this one is going to be made again STAT 🤤🤤🤤
WE ALL NEED TO KNOW- do you or do you not spit out the pomegranate seeds?!?!? 🤯

Let’s make some dinner!

I can barely count all the nutrient powerhouses in this one. Kale, sweet potatoes, ginger, paprika, cumin, extra virgin olive oil, red wine vinegar, pumpkin seeds, a bite of health that tastes AMAZE. 🤩

Warm ginger vinaigrette:
-1.5 teaspoons toasted sesame vinaigrette
-1/4 cup finely minced red onion
-1 inch knob of ginger, freshly grated
-3 tablespoons red wine vinegar
-1 tablespoon honey
-2 teaspoons coconut aminos (or soy sauce)
-3 tablespoons water
-1/3 cup extra virgin olive oil

Sauté the ginger and red onion in the toasted sesame oil over medium heat in a small saucepan until softened, about 5 minutes. Reduce heat to low. Add the red wine vinegar, honey, coconut aminos and water. Slowly whisk in the olive oil until emulsified.

Spiced sweet potatoes and chicken breast:
combine 1 teaspoon-ish of: smoked paprika, garlic powder, cumin, chipotle chile powder, kosher salt and fresh cracked pepper.

Chop 3 sweet potatoes into small cubes, drizzle with olive oil and add about 1/2 of the spice mixture, toss to combine and roast at 425 for 22-24 minutes until golden brown and crispy.

Slice two organic chicken breasts in half lengthwise so they are thin. Add the rest of the spice mixture to both size along with a drizzle of olive oil and squeeze of fresh lime. Cook in a cast iron skillet with a swish of oil for about 6 minutes per side until cooked through. Deglaze the pan with some red wine vinegar, scrape up the brown bits and then add it to your vinaigrette.

Salad:
-1 big bunch red curly kale, thinly sliced
-pepitas
-goat cheese

Drizzle a bit of dressing on the kale and massage for about 5 minutes. Pile in the kale, add sliced chicken breast, sweet potatoes, pepitas, goat cheese and more vinaigrette. DIG IN, IT’S SO GOOD.

I know kale is a lil polarizing… are you a kale person!? I absolutely love it. 🌱 This salad might just change your mind!

Do you make your own dressings!?

I was slightly intimidated at first but now that I’ve got it down, I hardly ever buy a premade dressing or vinaigrette at the store!

I love making my own because 1) I control all the ingredients and 2) the flavor is WAY bettah!

Here is the base recipe:
1 clove finely grated or minced garlic*
1 teaspoon dijon mustard
1 tablespoon agave, honey or maple syrup
1/4 teaspoon each sea salt and freshly ground pepper
3-4 tablespoons vinegar
1/2 cup good quality extra virgin olive oil

Simply shake all of these ingredients together until smooth and completely mixed together. You can use a jar with a lid or the salad shaker I’m using here is v clutch.

*I like to grate the garlic on a microplane so it melds seamlessly into the dressing

(both the salad shaker and microplane are linked under ‘kitchen essentials’ in my storefront, link in bio. these are fabulous gifts/stocking stuffers, just sayin’)

Variations:

-for an Asian vinaigrette use a tablespoon of toasted sesame oil plus a neutral flavored oil like avocado instead of olive plus freshly grated ginger

-add 2-3 tablespoons mayo or Greek yogurt for a creamy dressing (this works particularly well with a dijon-honey-apple cider vinegar base as a creamy honey mustard OR in a balsamic vinaigrette because creamy balsamic is 😚🤌🏼)

-for an Italian variation use red wine vinegar and add dried oregano, basil and a pinch of red pepper flakes

-for a Mexican vibe use 1/2 white vinegar, 1/2 lime juice, add fresh cilantro, finely diced jalapeño and agave as the sweetener

Let me know if this was helpful and make sure to tag me in your dressing creations!

This dinner was done in 20 min flat! 💯

1lb pork tenderloin, very thinly sliced*
1 inch knob of ginger, freshly grated
2 large cloves garlic, freshly grated
1 tablespoon chili garlic sauce
1-2 tablespoons brown sugar
3 tablespoons coconut aminos (or soy sauce!)

For serving:
Rice, veggies, green onions (I used bok choy, carrots and bell pepper)

Whisk or shake together the sauce. *if you put the pork in the freezer for about an hour it’s way easier to slice thin. Pour 2/3 of the sauce on the pork. Heat a swish of avocado oil in a pan over high heat. Cook the pork in two batches until caramelized and cooked through. Remove from pan, add the veggies and sauté until tender but still crisp, about 6 minutes. Toss with the rest of the sauce.

Serve over rice and top with green onions.

This recipe is from Magnolia journal which I recently got a subscription to 🤗 (in the video I’m doubling it)

1/2 cup granulated sugar
1/2 cup brown sugar
1/2 cup butter, softened
2 eggs
1 tsp vanilla
1/2 tsp peppermint extract
1/2 tsp instant espresso coffee powder
1/3 cup Dutch-process unsweetened cocoa powder
1 tsp baking soda
1/4 tsp salt
1 2/3 cup all-purpose flour
4oz dark chocolate, chopped
1/2 cup mint baking chips (I use Guittard brand)
chopped candy canes or candy cane kisses, for topping

1. Preheat oven to 375 degrees. In a large bowl beat sugars and butter on medium for 2 minutes. Beat in eggs, vanilla, peppermint and coffee powder until combined. Beat in cocoa powder, baking soda and salt until combined. Beat in flour. Stir in chopped chocolate and chips.
2. Drop dough by 1/4-cup portions 3 inches apart on parchment-lined cookie sheets. Bake 7 minutes. Remove cookie sheet and firmly tap three times on counter. Return to oven and bake 2 minutes more or until centers appear set. Repeat tapping. Let cool 2 minutes on cookie sheets.
3. Spread with chocolate peppermint ganache* and crushed candy cane kisses. 

*the chocolate peppermint ganache I had leftover from the brownies I made a few weeks ago, it is just 1 cup warmed heavy cream poured over 1.25c chocolate chips and 3/4 tsp peppermint extract, whisked together until smooth.

Listen, I’m not a Rice Krispie treat gal.

I make my ultimate chocolate peanut butter Rice Krispie treats once a year for camping but otherwise there are about a million other things I’d rather have as a treat.

But when I saw Lindsey of @pinchofyum make these salted caramel Rice Krispie bars I was like yeaaahhhh imma need those. So onto the holiday baking list they went!

Here’s the thing I think is key. I don’t want like an airy, sticky “light” Rice Krispie treat. I want a dense, chewy, buttery, soft bar with depth of flavor beyond marshmallow sweetness.

And that is EXACTLY what these are. Super compact texture (make sure to really presssss them into the pan), salty, caramelly and amazing.

All recipe credit to @pinchofyum, they are on her site called “salted caramel Rice Krispie bars”!

1 cup unsalted butter
1 cup lightly packed light brown sugar
1/2 cup heavy whipping cream
2 teaspoons flaky sea salt
10-ounce package miniature marshmallows (I used 16 ounces for extra gooey!)
12-ounce box of Rice Krispies or crispy rice cereal

Melt butter in a large pot over medium heat.
Add sugar and whipping cream; stir to incorporate. It will take a minute, but as it heats, you’ll start to see a smooth, creamy caramel mixture form. Heat over medium-low heat for 5-7 minutes, until you have a slightly thickened caramel sauce that coats the back of a spoon.
Remove from heat and stir in the salt. Taste and adjust for more salt if you want.
Add the marshmallows and stir until melted.
Stir in the cereal. Press mixture into a 9×13 pan. I like to like the pan with parchment with overhang on each side so I can easily pull them out of the pan to slice into bars.
Cool slightly, cut into squares, and enjoy! Serve at room temp or from the refrigerator!

Dark chocolate chunk oatmeal cookies!

I “vegan-ize” a lot of cookie recipes I make bc my sis is vegan and I love her to have some treats to enjoy too. The egg-free dough came in clutch for copious toddler finger-fuls of taste testing lol.

This recipe is from @sallysbakeblog but I made just a few modifications.

1 cup unsalted butter, softened to room temperature (I used earth balance)
1 cup packed light or dark brown sugar
1/4 cup granulated sugar
2 large eggs, at room temperature (I replaced with 2 tablespoons flaxseed mixed with 5 tablespoons warm water)
1 Tablespoon pure vanilla extract
1 Tablespoon molasses
1 and 1/2 cups all-purpose flour
1 teaspoon baking soda
1/2 teaspoon salt
3 cups old-fashioned whole rolled oats
1 1/2 cups dark chocolate chunks (I used @enjoylifefoods dairy free chunks)
1 added about 2/3 cup chopped walnuts and pecans
flaky sea salt for topping

Using a hand mixer or a stand mixer fitted with paddle attachment, cream the softened butter and both sugars together on medium speed until smooth, about 2 minutes. Add the eggs and mix on high until combined, about 1 minute. Scrape down the sides and bottom of the bowl as needed. Add the vanilla and molasses and mix on high until combined. Set aside.

In a separate bowl, whisk the flour, baking soda, cinnamon, and salt together. Add to the wet ingredients and mix on low until combined. Beat in the oats and chocolate on low speed. Chill the dough for 30-60 minutes in the refrigerator.

Roll balls of dough about 2 tablespoons each and place 2 inches apart on lined baking sheet. Bake at 350 for 11-12 minutes. Immediately sprinkle with flaky sea salt if using.

And our bellies were too full of dough to taste test the baked cookies (plus it was post-bedtime haha) but rest assured, they are DELISH!

Chocolate pb cookie cups are like the ever-so-classic peanut butter blossoms but better because peanut butter cup > hershey’s kiss amirite!?

It’s the same peanut butter cookie dough but baked in a mini muffin tin so you can easily squish in a peanut butter cup and the cookie encloses it perfectly!

This recipe is from allrecipes except I modified it with a flax egg, alternative milk and dairy free PB cups to make it egg and dairy free.

1 ¾ cups all-purpose flour
½ teaspoon salt
1 teaspoon baking soda
½ cup butter, softened
½ cup white sugar
½ cup peanut butter
½ cup packed brown sugar
1 egg, beaten (or flax egg! 1 T flaxseed + 2.5 T warm water)
1 teaspoon vanilla extract
2 tablespoons milk (I used almond milk)
40 miniature chocolate covered peanut butter cups, unwrapped (I used @justins dark choc pb cups)

Preheat oven to 375 degrees F. Mix together the flour, salt and baking soda; set aside.

Cream together the butter, sugar, peanut butter and brown sugar until fluffy. Beat in the egg, vanilla and milk. Add the flour mixture; mix well. Shape into 40 balls and place each into a greased mini muffin pan.

Bake at 375 degrees for about 8 minutes. Remove from oven and immediately press a mini peanut butter cup into each ball. Cool and carefully remove from pan.

I took it one tiny step further and drizzled with a little dark chocolate for the perfect finish!

These are sooooo dangggg good. Possibly my fave cookie yet?! Ugh impossible to choose!

What’s your sugar cookie personality?

Rolled out, cut into shapes and iced? Crisp and basic?
OR
Rolled into balls and coated in sugar or sprinkles. Soft, pillowy and a little chewy?

If you’re the latter, these are for you! I make these soft batch sugar cookies every Christmas and they are my husband’s number one pick out of all the holidays treats I make.

This recipe is from thesaltymarshmallow.com with just a few tiny modifications!

-1 Stick butter softened
-¼ Cup cream cheese softened
-1 ½ Cups granulated sugar
-2 Large eggs
-1 Teaspoon vanilla extract
-1 Teaspoon almond extract
-2 ½ Cups all purpose flour
-2 Teaspoons corn starch
-1 Teaspoon baking soda
-¼ Teaspoon salt
-1/2 cup sprinkles nonpareils
 
In bowl of stand mixer fitted with paddle attachment, or a large bowl using hand mixer, cream together the butter, cream cheese, sugar, eggs, and extracts until light and fluffy. About 5 minutes.
Scrape down the sides of the bowl with a spatula. Add the flour, corn starch, baking soda, and salt. Mix together on low/medium speed for one minute, until combined.
Refrigerate dough for two hours before baking.
When dough is done chilling, preheat oven to 350 degrees. Line two baking sheets with parchment paper or silicone baking mats.
Pour the sprinkles into a medium bowl, and roll tablespoon sized balls of dough into the sprinkles.
Place the cookies onto prepared baking sheet, spacing 2 inches apart.
Bake for 9-10 minutes. These should not turn golden brown, and will still look wet when they come out of the oven.
Allow cookies to cool on baking sheet for 3-5 minutes before moving to a wire rack to cool completely.

1lb wild caught mahi mahi (I buy the frozen from Costco), patted dry and seasoned with salt and pepper
1/2 cup flour
2 eggs, beaten
1/2 cup panko breadcrumbs
avocado oil

Heat oil in a good quality nonstick or stainless steel pan over medium high. Pan fry the fish for 1-2 minutes per side until deeply golden brown, about 10 min total.

hey hi I’m eating avocado toast.

but I filmed just so I could answer this FAQ.

“Why do you use mayo instead of butter?”

I’ve historically always hated mayo so this surprises even me lol.

But trust me when I say, it doesn’t TASTE like mayo, the mayo is purely for practical purposes of getting the bread perfectly toasted. 🤌🏼

Okay here are my reasons:

1️⃣ mayo is FAR more spreadable, getting just the slightest layer evenly distributed on both sides of the bread

2️⃣ mayo, which is made from oil, has a higher smoke point than butter, allowing you to have the heat higher to get the bread actually toasted without burning it

3️⃣ depending which mayo you use, you could save a few calories as some mayos have fewer calories per tablespoon than butter

4️⃣ depending on which mayo you use and what kind of oil it is primarily made from, you could be consuming more healthy monounsaturated fats vs the saturated fat in butter. I personally recommend avocado oil mayo.(@chosenfoods heyyyyy) A lot of mayo is made from extremely refined oils like soybean oil, so if you can make the switch to avocado oil mayo, I definitely recommend!

And there you have it! Those are my reasons!

Listen, no shade to butter, I do love butter too, but for every day BEST AVO TOAST IN THE LAND, my mayo griddled sourdough is the key. 💯

homemade hummus is the GOAT.

I mean, I do buy hummus occasionally because I don’t have my act together enough to make my own but my goodness each time I make from scratch I am reminded at how delicious and easy it is!

This recipe is from @cookieandkate and is titled “best hummus” and…it really is the best ever! (Modified slightly per my taste!)

1 can (15 oz) chickpeas, rinsed and drained, or 1 ½ cups cooked chickpeas
½ teaspoon baking soda (if you’re using canned chickpeas)
1 large lemon, juiced
2 medium-to-large clove garlic, roughly chopped
½ teaspoon fine sea salt, to taste
½ cup tahini
2 to 4 tablespoons ice water, more as needed
3/4 teaspoon ground cumin
1/2 t smoked paprika
1 tablespoon extra-virgin olive oil

Place the chickpeas in a medium saucepan in boiling water with the baking soda. Boil, reducing heat if necessary to prevent overflow, for about 20 minutes, or until the chickpeas look bloated, their skins are falling off, and they’re quite soft. In a fine-mesh strainer, drain the chickpeas and run cool water over them for about 30 seconds. Set aside (no need to peel the chickpeas)

Meanwhile, in a food processor or high-powered blender, combine the lemon juice and garlic. Process until the garlic is very finely chopped, then let the mixture rest so the garlic flavor can mellow, ideally 10 minutes or longer.

Add the tahini to the food processor and blend until the mixture is thick and creamy, stopping to scrape down any tahini stuck to the sides and bottom of the processor as necessary.

Add the cumin, salt and paprika and the drained, over-cooked chickpeas to the food processor. While blending, drizzle in the olive oil and 1-2 T water. Blend until the mixture is super smooth, scraping down the sides of the processor as necessary, about 2 minutes. Add more ice water by the tablespoon if necessary to achieve a super creamy texture.

Taste and season accordingly with more lemon, salt, cumin, etc!

I used to be TERRIBLE at making hard boiled eggs. Like so, so terrible, I hated it. I wasted half the egg just trying to peel the darn thing. But after years of trial and error I found a strategy that works for me!

This is how I do it:

First, place eggs in a saucepan of boiling water in a single layer. Reduce the heat to a constant simmer and cover with a tight fitting lid. Cook time will depend on how done you want the yolk: for soft boiled simmer for exactly 6.5 minutes, medium for 8 minutes and hard for 10 minutes. Take care not to overcook the eggs as that will result in a greenish-gray ring around the yolk which is caused by a chemical reaction between the iron in the yolk and the sulfur in the white. This is relatively harmless but overcooking also makes the eggs rubbery and can cause the eggshells to become more difficult to peel, as the whites can adhere tightly to the shell. 

While the eggs are simmering, fill a bowl with ice water. Use a slotted spoon to transfer them to the ice water bath. 

To peel the eggs, give them a smack and gentle roll on a hard surface, starting at the larger end of the egg where there is a small pocket of air. Cracking the egg on this end will force air up the sides of the egg, releasing the shell from the egg and making it easier to peel. 

Enjoy on its own, in salads, sandwiches, ramen or whatever you want! Super versatile and a great source of protein.

You know what’s been a bit frustrating to me lately?

The “busy wars.” Where every person on the internet competes to be the “busiest”. 

I’ve noticed in both my own comment section and other creators’ comment sections the comments like “wow it must be nice to have all that time” or “I could never, I’m way too busy” or my personal fave “you must not work” or “must be nice to not have to go to work”

Sigh.

There are a couple things to unpack here.

First, it never ceases to astound me how much people think they know about your life from watching a 60 second video of you making dinner. 🤯

Second, the people I know who have the career of content creator and/or mom are some of the busiest, hardest working people I know. And although their careers are not 9-5 in an office, they WORK, and they work hard.

Third, comparison is the thief of joy. And I know it’s hard, but you should really never compare yourself to anyone on the internet.

And finally, everyone has the exact same amount of time. I heard on a podcast recently that if you say you don’t have time for <insert thing here>, what you’re really saying is that <insert thing here> is not a priority to you.

And although this is a hard truth for me to hear, it is absolutely true. 

With some time management and planning I absolutely believe cooking and eating healthy can be realistic and attainable for every person. BUT you do have to be in a mental space where you really value and prioritize it.

And it absolutely does not have to take a lot of time, this dinner was done in 20 minutes!

Because right now I have two VERY sick girls, and I’m in survival mode. 😩 But Ka-La and I still have to eat so quick and easy to the rescue!

One of my FAVE quick and easy meals! Pepper pineapple chorizo brown rice bowls!

🫑beautiful antioxidant rich bell peppers
🧅sweet onion
🍍caramelized pineapple
🥓spicy chorizo
🍚whole grain brown rice
🥑heart-healthy avocado
🧂herbs and spices

Covering all your nutritional bases in one balanced bowl! ✅

Simply brown up some chorizo on medium high heat and set aside. Add 2 bell peppers and 1 sweet onion and cook until caramelized. Season with s&p and smoked paprika. Set aside. Add a touch of avocado oil to the pan and add about 2 cups diced pineapple. 
Don’t stir constantly, you want the pineapple to brown and caramelize a bit. Add the chorizo and veggies back in along with 1-2 cups of cooked brown rice (this is 1/2 cup dry brown rice, then cooked). Stir, add green onions. Top with creamy chipotle sauce (mayo + chipotle pepper in adobo + lime) and avocado slices.

Feel free to customize however you want! Use quinoa instead of brown rice, try chicken or vegetarian chorizo as a sub, use mango instead of pineapple, add more fresh herbs or a different kind of sauce. This really isn’t a recipe, it’s an idea 😂🤘🏼

And it is soooooo good and satisfying!!!

I am a strict once a week shopper. I make a list of everything I will need for the next 7 days and then make it a priority to eat everything I purchased so that little to nothing goes to waste.

My Costco hauls generally include stock-ups of things like wild caught salmon, shrimp, organic chicken breast, eggs, chicken sausage and organic ground beef which is often why you don’t see a ton of animal-based protein in my week-to-week hauls. Once again this is a bit of an oversimplification but for illustration purposes let’s take this week’s spend ($139) plus let’s say $80 worth in protein/pantry staples I already have.

139 + 80 = $219 for the week

3 meals x 4 people x 7 days = 84

Do you make your own dressings at home?!

I am a “from scratch” girlie when it comes to most sauces and dressings. They really are so simple and taste SO much better than storebought. Plus, you have control over what goes in so you can modify however you like!

I love a balsamic vinaigrette, it’s so versatile and when made with quality ingredients it just can’t be beat.

Also, COMPLETELY OPTIONAL, and I don’t always add but a spoonful or two of mayo takes this dressing over the top!

Here’s my base recipe:
1 teaspoon Dijon mustard
1-2 teaspoons honey or agave
1-2 tablespoons mayo (optional)
1/4 cup balsamic vinegar
1/2 cup good quality extra virgin olive oil*
Generous pinches of sea salt and cracked black pepper 

Whisk or blend ingredients until completely smooth. Taste and season to taste if needed.

*not refined olive oil, not “light olive oil”, not “olive oil”, get “extra virgin olive oil” The one from Costco is ranked really high in consumer reports for quality!

Pesto burrata tomato sandwich is just… ugh it’s just everything I want in a sandwich and more. 

Fresh flavorful pesto, peppery arugula tossed with balsamic vinaigrette, juicy tomatoes seasoned with flaky sea salt and creamy burrata cheese, all piled on focaccia. 

Thanks to @hipfoodiemom1 for the inspo!!

Pesto:
1/4 cup toasted pine nuts
2 large cloves garlic
1/4 cup finely grated parmesan cheese
3oz fresh basil leaves
salt and pepper
juice of 1/2 lemon
1/3 cup extra virgin olive oil
3-4 tablespoons cold water

In a food processor pulse the pine nuts, garlic and parmesan cheese until coarsely ground. Add the basil, salt, pepper and lemon. Process and with the motor running stream in the olive oil and then add water a tablespoon at a time until desired consistency is reached. You can replace the water with more olive oil but I like to use a little water to loosen it to cut down some on the fat/calories.

For the sandwiches:
🍞focaccia or any bread you enjoy!
🌱pesto
🍅tomatoes seasoned with flaky sea salt and fresh cracked pepper
🧀8oz ball burrata
🥬arugula tossed with balsamic vinaigrette (see previous vid!)
🖤balsamic glaze
🌱fresh basil

Assemble the sandwiches by layering on pesto, tomatoes, burrata (just burst open the ball and spread it around), arugula, fresh basil and a final drizzle of balsamic glaze!

Double protein double cheesy eggs!? 😋✔️

I recently saw a few of my favorite dietitians, @nutritionalsarah and @zachcoen, add cottage cheese to their eggs to bump up the protein and cheesiness and I APPROVE. This combo has been on repeat all week.

I could go on and on about the importance of protein in the morning- not only is it satisfying and energizing for your day but it plays such a tremendous role in appetite regulation throughout the entire day and evening.

If you are a person who has a raging appetite in the evening or maybe you struggle with endless snacking after dinner, it might be time to evaluate what you’re eating for breakfast. You want to make sure you are eating a breakfast that is rich in protein, balanced and satisfying and micronutrient-dense.

This scramble of spinach, 2 eggs, about 1/4 cup cottage cheese and 1-2 tablespoons sharp cheddar has 21g protein! Add the English muffin and we’re up to 27g! 🙌🏼

And macros (aka protein, fat and carbs) are great and all but what I really nerd out about is getting as many MICROS into my meals as possible. Micronutrients are nutrients that don’t contribute calories but are SO important to your health. In this meal for example, the vitamin A and folate in spinach, anthocyanins and polyphenols in pomegranate and blackberries, choline in eggs, calcium in cheese and B vitamins in the English muffin.

So, not only is this meal satisfying calorie/macro-wise but by including fruits, veggies and other whole foods, we’re covering a LOT more nutrient bases! 💯

Do you have this mindset when it comes to food? For me, it’s all about what I can ADD, not what I have to limit or restrict!

Also, def try these protein cheesy eggs stat. 🔥

This cashew queso sauce 😩🤌🏼💯🔥🤤

Vegan, gluten-free and dairy free but honestly I don’t care about any of those things because it is DELICIOUS AND AMAZING. I’ve been making this for years for ANY Mexican-inspired dishes, I love it so much.

1 cup cashews
1 chipotle pepper in adobo sauce
2 tablespoons nutritional yeast
1-2 teaspoons taco seasoning
1/2 teaspoon salt
1 4oz can fire roasted diced green chiles
1/4-1/2 cup water

Soak the cashews in extra warm water for 10-15 minutes. You can technically make this without soaking but soaking makes it SUPAH creamy. Add cashews and all other ingredients to a high powered blender (I use the cup attachment for my Vitamix) and blend on high until very very smooth.

Taste and adjust with more salt for general flavor, adobo sauce for more spice or nutritional yeast for more umami/cheesiness. Start with 1/4 cup water but you may have to add a touch more until your desired consistency is reached.

Use on tacos, burrito bowls, nachos or just straight up on chips or veggies!

Drink. of. the. week!! 💦
 
Cucumber mint lime sparkler!
 
There are a few recommendations for the amount of water needed to stay hydrated- two of the most popular are 64oz OR half your body weight in ounces.
 
We as a nation, do not drink enough water. We’re all walking around chronically dehydrated. And it’s crazy how much dehydration can affect us.
 
Example: So yesterday, I co-taught a spin class in the morning. And I went HARD. And one thing about me, is I sweat. Like I truly sweat buckets when I exercise. I’m not like a dainty exerciser that has her hair down and wears earrings and might have a slight flush to my cheeks. Nah friends. Ya girl sweats. 
 
Anywaaayyy, I sweat a TON yesterday morning and I did not hydrate enough before, during or after my workout. Then it was 4pm and I had a massive headache, I was lethargic, hungry but not hungry? and just sooooo cranky.
 
And it was 100% from lack of water. And honestly by that point, it’s too late to just start chugging. it’ll help but it won’t completely solve your problem.
 
The best way is to hydrate consistently, all the time, especially BEFORE a hard sweaty workout. 
 
And the best beverage for hydration you ask?
 
WATER.
 
Not gatorade. not coconut water. not fancy electrolyte mixes. 

Water.

Guys I get this question alllll the time- “but water doesn’t have electrolytes.”
 
No, but know what does? Food. And we can get allll the electrolytes we need from a well-balanced diet.
 
Listen, I am not talking about the small percentage of the population that are intense endurance athletes that exercise for 2-4 hours a day (yes, they may need some supplementation of extra electrolytes, etc) 
 
But for the average person, even for a person like myself that exercises hard and daily, WATER is the key.
 
So, if you’re a person that struggles a bit with drinking water, here’s a fun way I like to jazz it up!
 
cucumber slices + fresh mint + lime slices plus fresh lime juice + ice + sparkling mineral water

and guess what mineral water DOES have sodium, potassium, magnesium and calcium so it’s just a win overall.
 
How much water do you drink a day? Like true, plain water (sparkling or flat)? 👇🏼💦

Here are my questions of the evening:

1. Do you believe that “healthy eating” is less flavorful, fun or yummy than say, convenience foods or takeout?

2. Do you believe healthy foods are significantly more expensive than takeout/convenience?

3. Do you think that healthy eating takes more time than takeout/convenience?

I think you all pretty much know where I’m headed with this and my personal answers to these questions.

Being in my line of work has made it very apparent just how many people think a healthy lifestyle is a mythical, out-of-reach scenario. And honestly with social media how it is with influencers and their spendy supplements and $17 smoothies and $30 salads and $200 juice cleanses, yeah, I mean who can blame a person for believing this.

But, I’m here to deconstruct this narrative please.

This meal included lean protein, satisfying carbs and nutritious veggies. It was extremely quick to make, inexpensive and tasted amazing.

Proof that healthful eating does not need to be complicated, time-consuming or bland.

Here’s what I did!

Cucumber Salad:
dressing-
▪️3 teaspoons coconut aminos (or soy sauce, they are v similar!)
▪️2 tablespoons seasoned rice vinegar
▪️1 tablespoon toasted sesame oil
▪️1/4 teaspoon salt
▪️2 teaspoons sugar
other-
▪️cucumbers (a mix if you can! I used 1/2 an english cucumber and 1 pint baby cucumbers)
▪️3 cloves minced garlic
▪️1 spoonful chili crunch (I used Momofuku)
▪️green onions
▪️sesame seeds

Whisk together the dressing. Smash the cucumbers! Just chop into chunks and then use the flat side of your chef knife to give them a smash. You can smash the baby ones whole and then give a rough chop. Toss cukes with dressing. Add the garlic, green onions, chili crunch and sesame seeds.

Shrimp:
pat 1lb shrimp dry and season generously with salt and pepper. Heat a swish of avocado oil over medium high heat. Sauté shrimp for 90 seconds per side until pink and cooked through. Add some minced garlic and a couple splashes of toasted sesame oil.

Plate the shrimp and cucumber salad with your grain of choice like quinoa, brown or jasmine rice!

Welcome to salads that don’t suck-the series where we make epically delicious salads that you truly want to eat.

Enter: crunchy ramen salad w/ honey lime vinaigrette.

Tons of hearty, antioxidant-rich veggies, crunchy ramen noodles, roasted cashews, creamy avocado, perfectly sweet mango and the simplest honey lime vinaigrette packed with healthy fats makes for a salad that you will not tire of eating.

Let’s talk about the dressing. Did you know that many of the vitamins in vegetables are best utilized and absorbed when consumed with a source of fat? So fat-free salad dressings be gone, prioritize making a simple dressing from scratch with a healthy fat oil like @chosenfoods 100% Pure Avocado Oil. I love @chosenfoods because it is a quality, naturally refined avocado oil that has a very neutral taste (perfect for dressings) AND can be used at high temps (perfect for sautéing and roasting at high heat)

For the dressing whisk together:
-1/2 cup @chosenfoods avocado oil
-1/4 cup honey
-2 tablespoons rice vinegar
-2 tablespoons coconut aminos (or soy sauce!)
-juice of a lime
-pinch of salt and fresh cracked pepper

Then for the salad you’ll need:
-finely shredded cabbage (I like to do this on the thinnest setting of my food processor slicing blade!)
-julienned carrots 
-1/2 english cucumber, diced
-1 bell pepper, diced
-1 cup edamame
-1 mango, diced
-1 avocado, cubed
-1/2 bunch scallions, sliced
-1/2 bunch cilantro, chopped
-2 packets ramen, seasoning packets discarded
-1 cup cashews

Crush up the ramen. Place noodles and cashews on a lined baking tray and roast at 400 for a total of 8 minutes, stirring at the 5 minute mark.

Throw all salad ingredients together, douse with dressing and toss it up! Serve w/ additional protein like grilled chicken, shrimp or tofu, if desired. (this is wonderful on its own though!)

This is probably my number one favorite meal prep salad. Because the base is hearty shredded cabbage, and not lettuce, it holds up SO well for up to 5 days! Just keep the dressing on the side.

Chili for chilly day! What is the temp right now where you’re at? It’s currently 30 degrees Fahrenheit for us, so a hearty bowl of chili is still VERY much on the menu.

And WHITE chili!? yummmmm. A mixture of veggies, corn, white beans and chickpeas, fire roasted chiles and creamy cashew queso made for a truly delicious bowl of plant-based chili!

This was a fabulous way to use up my leftover cashew queso sauce (remember from last week??) but if you didn’t have that you could absolutely use heavy cream or sour cream instead.

Here’s how to make it! 

1 tablespoon olive oil
1 sweet bell pepper, diced
1 sweet onion, diced
4 garlic cloves, minced
1 teaspoon each kosher salt, fresh cracked pepper, smoked paprika, cumin, dried oregano
1 4oz can diced fire roasted green chiles
1 can white beans, drained and rinsed
1 can cannellini beans, drained and rinsed
1 can chickpeas, drained and rinsed
2 ½ to 3 cups vegetable stock
1 cup corn (frozen, canned or fresh)
½ cup vegan cashew queso (what I used) OR heavy cream
for topping: fresh cilantro, green onions, sour cream, tortilla chips, avocado, cheese, lime juice, etc

In large stockpot or dutch oven sauté the bell pepper, garlic and onions over medium heat until softened and caramelized, about 7 minutes. Add all the spices and stir around so they “bloom” in flavor- when making soups you want to always add your seasonings to the hot oil/veggies BEFORE adding the liquid!

Then add the green chiles, beans, stock and corn. Cover and let simmer for 20-30 minutes. Using an immersion blender, pulse just a few times. This helps create a smooth thickness, but don’t blend too much because you still want quite a lot of that bean and veggie texture!

Add cashew sauce or heavy cream and stir. Top with alllll the things- green onions, avocado and big squeeze of lime for me!

I served with @kodiakcakes protein packed cornbread and both were absolutely divine. SUCH a satisfying meal.

I’ve mentioned this a few times in the past but I’m really not a bar girl. As in granola bar. These are often promoted as “healthy snacks” and some bars are probably great, not demonizing bars here, but when I’m hungry and eat a bar…I’m still hungry. 💁🏻‍♀️😆 So as far as snacks go I much prefer a handful of nuts, piece of fruit, veggies with hummus, toast with peanut butter, etc.

BUT. When I can find the time to sneak in making a batch of these energy bites?!? Omg yaaaassss. They’re kinda like a homemade granola bar? But way way better.

And to be honest, there is no wrong way to make these. It’s a…fluid process. Too dry? Add more pb or honey. Too wet? Add more oats. Don’t have hemp hearts? Try chia or flax seed. Allergic to peanuts? Try sunflower seed butter. Don’t like coconut? What is wrong with you. Jk jk just leave it out.

See? You can totally make it your own.

Here’s the rough-ish measurements I used!
2 cups oats
1 cup flaked coconut (you can use unsweetened or sweetened)
1/2 cup all natural peanut butter (creamy or crunchy!)
1/2 cup honey (you can sub maple or agave)
1/4 cup hemp hearts
Pinch of salt
1/2 cup mini chocolate chips
melted dark chocolate and flaky sea salt, for topping

Pulse the coconut and oats in a food processor until finely ground. Add the rest of the ingredients except the chocolate chips. Blend until a thick dough forms, if it seems too dry just add a little more nut butter or honey. Move mixture to a bowl and fold in the chocolate chips. You don’t want to add the chips to the food processor bc they’ll get all crushed up and melty and end up more like a chocolate pb ball instead of a pb ball with choc chips.

Drizzle with some dark chocolate and sprinkle with flaky sea salt. omg.

Place in the fridge or freezer to harden. I keep these in the freezer and snag a few whenever I need a snack. They’re good for up to 4 months in the freezer.

This is my PERFECT afternoon pick-me-up/treat with a cup of tea!

I need to show you guys a magic trick.

It’s called… make your own nut butter. 

nuts➡️food processor➡️nut butter➡️life changed.

What is a jar of cashew butter running these days? $15ish? I mean granted, cashews are expensive too, but take $7 of cashews and make them into a glorious creamy $15 worth of cashew butter? magic.

And it’s also magic because we set it and forget it, old school crockpot style ya know?

Dump cashews in a food processor, hit go and go about your day.

You’ll have to stop to scrape down the sides of the processor a few times. And your cashews will throw a couple tantrums- they’ll look all dry and crumbly, then bunch into a ball and make your food processor almost tip over, but then they will smooth out into a gorgeous, creamy butter.

Listen to me. I added a pinch of flaky sea salt. That’s IT. Let me say that again, I did not add anything to this. When you see it all dry and crumbly do not freak out and add oil or water or syrup or ANYTHING. This is the most common mistake people ask me about when making homemade nut butters.  Be patient. It’ll get there. 

Add roasted cashews to a food processor (if your cashews are not roasted, I highly recommend/insist that you roast them first, 15 minute at 300, it’ll make your nut butter come together MUCH easier and the result will be drippier and creamier). Press go and periodically scrape down the sides. Add a pinch of flaky sea salt. Process until smooth. It’ll take about 10-15 minutes.

Store in a jar at room temp and go CRAY. This will not last more than a week I assure you. But it does stay good for several months.

I have the cuisinart elemental 13 cup food processor and it is by and far, my favorite kitchen “thing.” If I could only have one kitchen gadget it would 100% be my food processor. It is so versatile. I have it linked in my storefront under kitchen appliances (link in my bio and story) and right now it’s actually 15% off PLUS a $20 off coupon! 💯

Happy Heart Health Month! 🫀

One thing I cannot emphasize enough is the importance of an ADD (not restrict!) mindset for health. 

In the nutrition world there is far too much emphasis on everything you need to restrict or cut out and not enough education on how ADDING can actually make the biggest, most sustainable change to your balanced lifestyle and wellness. #ad 

Americans consume too much sodium. Period. And there are some pretty scary risks that accompany a high sodium diet including increased blood pressure and increased risk for heart disease and stroke. So it is absolutely necessary that we address the sodium in our diets. 

However, no salt does NOT mean no flavor. Finding flavorful ingredients that do not contain salt can help lower sodium in the diet. 

Enter: @knorr Zero Salt Boullion. A super flavorful seasoning to favor your heart and flavor your food! 

Let’s take the ramen example. We’d like to reduce the sodium of this meal and make it more balanced so we ADD: 

-Knorr Zero Salt Chicken Bouillon plus lots of garlic and ginger as our flavor base 
-seared bok choy in a little toasted sesame oil 
-caramelized mushrooms (sauté in a swish of toasted sesame oil over medium high heat for about 10 minutes, until all the water is evaporated and they are deeply caramelized)
-chopped green onions marinated with a splash of coconut aminos and spoonful of chili crunch 
-a perfectly soft boiled egg for protein 

Giving us a balanced, sodium conscious, nutrient dense meal that’ll keep us satisfied!

You can find Knorr Zero Salt Bouillon at your local grocer, I highly recommend you give it a try!  

Tell me in the comments your favorite ways to add flavor without salt/sodium!? 👇🏼

Never had I ever… made (or even eaten) French onion soup 😳🤯

Idk it’s just not something I was ever exposed to or something I thought to make or order!

But for this week’s meal plan I decided to change that! I had some mushrooms leftover that didn’t get eaten last week and I was trying to think of some way to use them. And obvi French onion soup doesn’t usually include mushrooms but I thought they would go wonderfully (which they did! And more veg is always a win in my book!)

I deviated from traditional in a couple ways with the mushrooms and the splash of cream but it just felt right…and it was so so good.

Here’s how I made it!
2 tablespoons salted butter
1 tablespoon extra virgin olive oil
5 medium sweet onions, thinly sliced
1 teaspoon salt
1 teaspoon brown sugar
1 cup dry white wine
4 cloves garlic, minced
1 teaspoon dried thyme
1 teaspoon all purpose seasoning
½ teaspoon cracked black pepper
2 cups mushrooms, sliced
4 cups chicken or veggie broth (I used my homemade!)
2 bay leaves
3-4 tablespoons heavy cream
Sliced French baguette
shredded Gruyère cheese
 
Heat butter and oil in a large dutch oven. Add onions and saute for 20-30 minutes, seasoning with salt and brown sugar, until deeply caramelized (this takes a while so be patient!) Add the mushrooms, garlic and seasonings and saute another 10 minutes. Add the wine ¼ cup at a time, letting it evaporate out after each addition. Add the broth and bay leaves and simmer for several minutes. Finish with a splash of cream. Slice the baguette and place in the oven at 400 degrees for 10 minutes until the bread is very toasty. Ladle soup into oven safe bowls, top with crusty bread slices, pile on some gruyere cheese. Return to oven and broil for 3 minutes.
 
OMG.
 
If you  have fresh thyme I recommend using fresh, but my grocery store didn’t have any 🫤

It is frigid outside but I’ll be curled up by the fire with this bowl of cozy deliciousness! 🧅🧄🥖🥣

If you haven’t made crispy kale and potatoes in the air fryer- let me convince you to start. 

First, drizzle potatoes with a little olive oil and I love to season them with @knorr Zero Salt Roasted Garlic Bouillon. #ad Bouillon is usually used like broth for soup, stews or casseroles but I love to use it as an all purpose seasoning that provides a ton of robust flavor without the salt! 

Pop the potatoes in the air fryer at 400 for 15 minutes, then repeat the oil and seasoning for some chopped kale and add to the basket to cook another 4 minutes. The potatoes and kale will be super crispy and oh so delish.

In a food environment where it is so easy to over-consume sodium, it is really important to be more conscious of our sodium intake. Too high sodium intake is associated with a myriad of health risks including increased blood pressure and increased risk of heart disease. 

What are some actionable steps you can take to manage sodium levels? 

1. use seasonings like Knorr Zero Salt Bouillon in place of some or all salt and/or high sodium seasonings  
2. cook at home, prioritizing balanced meals where you have control over the ingredients  
3. increase your intake of potassium-rich foods like potatoes, dark leafy greens, avocado, winter squash, bananas, many dried fruits and beans  

and hello, this meal is a REAL winner- we’ve slashed our sodium by using Knorr Zero Salt Roasted Garlic Bouillon AND we’ve included potassium powerhouses (ahem, potatoes, dark leafy greens, avocado…)

On top of our crispy hash I added: 2 fried eggs, creamy chipotle sauce (just mix a little mayo, lime juice and chipotle pepper in adobo!), green onions, crumbled feta and pickled jalapeños. 

Would you eat this for breakfast, lunch or dinner? My answer is all three. 

You can find Knorr Zero Salt Bouillon at your local grocery store to try for yourself! #favoryourheart #flavoryourfood #knorrpartner

Alright it’s about that time, time to make another jar of salted caramel!! 🤩

I’ve shown how to make this several times but I always get questions so here we go. Me and caramel have been on a journey and I have messed it up soooo many times…

-got scared and took it off the heat too soon so it was basically just a white syrup
-burned the 🤬 out of it and ended up with a black hard mess
-let the sugar crystals build up too much on the sides which made the sugar seize
-accidentally stirred it, again making the sugar seize into a clump
….I could go on 😐

But now I’ve got it down and I’m going to share with you all EXACTLY how to make it:

You need:
1 cup sugar
1/4 cup water
3/4 cup heavy cream
3 1/2 tablespoons butter
1 teaspoon pure vanilla
1 teaspoons sea salt (I’m a little aggressive on the salt bc that salty sweet is SO GOOD)

Combine the sugar and water over medium heat in a large, heavy bottomed sauce pan and stir to combine. This is the ONLY time you will stir, after the initial stir don’t you dare touch it again.

Next, we wait for the sugar to burn. That’s what caramel is! It’s going to start to boil. This is where the sugar crystal management comes in. That’s what you see me doing with the pastry brush. There will be some sugar crystals that accumulate on the sides of the pan. Take a wet pastry brush and gently wipe so that those crystals don’t build up. You want them to dissolve back into the mixture.

You want the sugar to get a deep deep golden brown. If you pull it too soon it won’t have caramel flavor but if you let it go too long it will taste burnt. The color you see me get too is exactly where you want it to be. Once it has reached that point (usually takes about 10 min) turn off the heat and add the heavy cream. Stir stir stir! It’s going to steam like crazy, try not to burn your hand off. Add the butter, keep stirring! Next add the vanilla and salt. If you have a few sugar clumps that’s ok, just turn the heat back to low and stir them until dissolved.

Pour into a jar and BOOM. Decadent, amazing, homemade salted caramel that is better than anything you’ll get in the store!

I drizzled some in a jar, added ice, espresso & oat milk…OMG 🤤☕️

The crispy sticky sweet chicken. the pickled veggies. the spicy mayo. the crunchy onions. the HERB SALAD. I just cannot, it’s so freaking good. 😩🤌🏼

This style of meal is the one I just make over and over because it is my favorite.

Rice bowls are life, who agrees!?

Here’s how to make:

Pickled veggies:
Dissolve together 1 cup apple cider vinegar, 1/3 cup honey, 1 teaspoon salt and 1/2 cup water. You can do this on the stovetop or microwave for 60 seconds and whisk until salt and honey are dissolved. Pour over sliced cucumbers and julienned carrots.

Spicy mayo:
Combine mayo, sriracha and fresh lime juice to taste. I like the ratio of 5 tablespoons of mayo to 1 tablespoon sriracha to 1/2 lime but it’s going to depend on your desired level of heat!

Chicken:
Whisk together 1/3 cup coconut aminos (or soy sauce or tamari), 1 tablespoon fish sauce, 1/4 cup honey, 2 teaspoons sriracha or chili garlic sauce and 1/3 cup water. Add a swish of avocado oil over medium high heat and brown organic ground chicken. Add four cloves chopped garlic and sauté for a minute. Drain excess water if needed. Add the sauce, reserving a few tablespoons for serving, if desired. Simmer allll the way until sauce is reduced and sticky and the chicken is caramelized (about 15 minutes).

Herb salad:
Toss together fresh green onions, mint, basil, cilantro with a touch of toasted sesame oil, fresh lime juice and salt. THIS IS THE BEST PART TRUST ME.

Assemble:
Fluffy steamed jasmine rice, sticky caramelized chicken, herb salad, pickled veggies, crunchy onions, sesame seeds, spicy mayo.

These rice bowls are inspired by @halfbakedharvest!

This meal will send you straight to flavor heaven. You’re welcome.

When in doubt…just start chopping vegetables 🥦🍠🧅🫑

Then throw ‘em on a sheet pan. Drizzle with olive oil. Throw on your favorite seasonings. Roast at 425-450 for 22-25 minutes (I give a range bc all ovens are different) Pair with a protein. Add a whole grain if desired. Jazz it up a lil and boom. Dinner done.

1 red bell pepper, 1/2 red onion, 2 Ataulfo mangos, 1 avocado, green onions, cilantro, juice of a lime, squeeze of honey, sprinkle of salt, pinch red pepper flakes (I would’ve used a jalapeño but I forgot to put it on my list) 

Toss finely shredded cabbage with some lime, salt and olive oil.

Take the skin off your salmon (I like to stick with wild sustainably caught Alaskan salmon from Costco), cut into cubes, season with taco seasoning and sauté in a little olive oil until cooked through- about 8-10 min.

Layer up! Crispy tortilla- cabbage slaw- seasoned salmon- mango pico- spicy mayo- squeeze of lime.

Are you a sweet or savory breakfast person?

For example, sweet people like oatmeal and yogurt and smoothies, etc. while savory people might opt for more eggs, potatoes, avocado, toast…

NGL I used to be a sweet gal all the way but I’ve done somewhat of a 180 and my hungry self almost always craves savory in the morning. I mean, I still do a mix of both (hellooooo breakfast banana split from a few days ago omg) but out of all my videos on this app roughly 17% of them are avocado toast. 😂😅

But listen, HAVE YOU TRIED CHILI OIL EGGS YET!? It took me way to long to hop on this trend but dear goodness. so freaking good.

I added a spoonful of Momofuku chili crunch to my pan, added two eggs straight into the oil for 1-2 minutes per side and boom! Savory, spicy and perfect.

My avocado toast is made per usual, very thin spread of good quality mayo on each side of a slice of sourdough, then griddled in the pan for about 3-4 minutes per side, until super crispy. I am telling you, this is the KEY factor. Do not use your toaster.

Then smashed up some avocado with lemon and salt. Added crumbled feta and EBTB seasoning. Chili oil eggs on top, fresh fruit on the side, piping hot coffee and THIS IS GONNA BE A GOOD DAY.

Pasta lovers unite!

Spaghetti ranks up there as one of top faves for my toddler and baby so it is one we have in consistent rotation.

Last fall, my sister made me arrabbiata. And I was quite literally shook by how amazingly delicious it was for how dang simple it was to make.

It has since become one of my favorite “in a pinch” recipes. It takes literally 15 minutes to prep and then you can simmer until ready to eat! In my case the sauce is prepped during nap and then served up at dinner time but you could make the sauce literally whenever you have 15 minutes to spare in your day and then when dinnertime chaos rolls around you’re ready to go!

Paired with a simple side salad and it’s a plant-based, nutrient-dense, super satisfying dinner that the whole fam enjoys. I made a salad with lettuce, pickled carrots, pepitas, homemade croutons and my homemade Caesar dressing (recipe on my blog!!)

For the arrabiata sauce you need:
* 1/4 cup extra virgin olive oil
* 1/2 sweet onion, finely chopped
* 6 cloves garlic, grated or minced
* 1 28oz can San Marzano tomatoes
* 1 teaspoon red pepper flakes OR 1 tablespoon chili onion crunch
* 1/2 teaspoon each kosher salt and fresh cracked pepper

The whole San Marzano tomatoes are KEY here. Please don’t mess around with any other type. Like a noob I spent $8.49 for one can at the grocery store but then one of my lovely followers told me that Costco sells a three pack for $9.99 so for SURE grab that next time you’re there!

The full written recipe, plus ideas on what to serve with, FAQ, ingredient substitutions and other tips is on my blog! Follow the link in my bio!

Also something I learned while writing this post: It is technically spelled Arrabbiata, with a double “b”, but apparently Americans just chronically spell it wrong so when you google a recipe, ‘arrabiata’ is the preferred spelling… so anyway yeah… one b or two, it’s delicious and you should try it. 🤤🔥

Guys! I’m excited to partner with Open Nature® to help spread the word on the incredible variety of products they offer. Whenever I shop at my local @Safeway, I always reach for Open Nature products because it is a brand I trust to be top quality. I was able to snag a variety of fresh veggies and this #OpenNature 100% grassfed top sirloin to make a beautifully balanced steak stir-fry. Served with brown rice and millet noodles (for extra protein and fiber!) and lots of sauce.

Here’s how to make!
Chop your veg:
-1 carrot, julienned
-2 bell peppers, sliced
-1/2 sweet onion, sliced
-2 cups broccoli florets (1 small head)
-8oz snap peas
-1 bunch green onions

Whisk together your sauce:
-4 cloves garlic, minced
-1 inch knob ginger, grated
-1 cup chicken or beef broth
-1/3 cup coconut aminos (or soy sauce!)
-2 T rice vinegar
-3-4 T honey
-2 T cashew or peanut butter (optional, but recommended)
-3 T corn starch whisked together with 3 T water
Season your meat:
-0.75-1lb Open Nature Top Sirloin
-salt, pepper, onion salt
-avocado oil
For serving:
-millet brown rice noodles (or any noodles or rice that you like)
-green onions, sriracha, cashews, sesame seeds

Chop the veg. Whisk together the sauce. Tenderize your steak with a meat mallet (or frying pan!), slice very thinly against the grain and season generously with salt, pepper and onion salt. Add a swish of avocado oil to a cast iron pan and fry over high heat for 2-3 minutes per size until browned. Remove meat and deglaze the pan with a little broth. Add the veggies, stir-frying until crisp tender, about 8 minutes. Reduce heat to low, pour in the sauce, add the meat and let simmer until sauce is thickened, this only takes a few minutes. Add noodles and toss to combine. Top with green onions, sriracha, cashews and sesame seeds!

And making one of my favorite meals ever.

If you’ve been following me for any length of time you’ve probably seen me make some iteration of this.

Sometimes I use zucchini and tomatoes. Sometimes I use butternut squash and kale. Today I used sweet potato and brussels sprouts. Sometimes I use orzo, sometimes couscous, today brown rice and quinoa. But the constant? Creamy garlic cashew sauce and fried feta omgggg.🤤

Conventional nutrition wisdom says to incorporate more beans/legumes and other plant-based sources of protein, prioritize whole grains, eat more nuts and seeds and significantly bump up veggie intake. And these are dietary habits we can all benefit from.

On paper, eating more beans, whole grains, nuts and vegetables might not sound very fun or tasty.

But I want to show you is that IT CAN BE. and this meal is a case in point.

Here’s how to make it:

Roast up some veg and garbanzo beans you’ve rinsed and patted dry. Anything veg you like. 425 for 25 minutes is a good starting place. Season with whatever you like- I used good quality olive oil, salt, pepper and green goddess seasoning.

Soak 1 cup roasted cashews in hot water for 10 minutes. Then drain and rinse and blend together with 2 cloves garlic, salt and pepper, juice of 1/2 lemon, 2 T olive oil and 2-3 T water. I use the cup attachment on my Vitamix, you’ll want a high powered blender to get it super smooth.

Cut a block of feta into planks. Coat with a bit of cornstarch and shake off the excess. Pro tip: place your feta in the freezer for 10 minutes before frying. Then add a swish of olive oil to a good-quality ceramic-coated nonstick pan. Fry over high heat for about 90 seconds per side. You want high heat and FAST, or else the feta will melt!

Then layer it up:
-creamy cashew sauce
-brown rice and quinoa (I used an easy steamable bag!)
-roasted veg
-raosted garbanzo beans
-microgreens
-fresh mint
-chopped pistachios
-fried feta
-balsamic glaze
-olive oil
-flaky sea salt

Okay hands in the air if you need a fun way to switch up plain ole chicken!?

This is it. Honey mustard chicken quinoa bowls.

So…I didn’t meal plan or grocery shop this week. 😳 I know, WUT. Sunday was my birthday and I spent it with the fam instead of doing my regular routine of meal planning, grocery shopping, washing and storing, etc.

So this week I’m just kinda wingin’ it. Ka-La had to get dog food so he ran to Costco and also grabbed berries, bananas, spinach, avocados and asparagus so those are the fresh items that will get us through the week (plus a few residual veggies from last week).

Anyway, I hate not having a plan. Nap time comes and I’m like CRAP what am I even making!?

When that happens this is what I do:

1. grab a protein from the freezer (enter: organic chicken breast)
2. look in the pantry for a grain (enter: quinoa)
3. make sure to prioritize any veggies I have on hand (asparagus, broccoli and sweet potato tots from the freezer!)
4. think up a fun sauce to give the dinner some fun and flavor

And that’s how this dinner was born.

First, whisk until super smooth:
-1/4 cup grainy mustard
-1/4 cup honey
-2 T apple cider vinegar
-2 T fresh lemon juice
-1/4 cup good quality mayo
-fresh cracked sea salt and pepper

The tots don’t need oil or seasoning but I coated the green veggies in a drizzle of olive oil and salt and pepper. Feel free to use any veg/seasonings you like!

I roasted everything at 450 for 18 minutes. (I’d actually recommend giving the broccoli and tots a 10 minute head start and then add the asparagus for the final 8 minutes)

Chop up chicken breast and marinate with a squeeze of lemon, salt, pepper and olive oil. When ready to cook add to a hot skillet and cook until browned, about 10 minutes total. 

Reduce temp and add about 1/3 of the sauce, stirring to coat the chicken.

I like to cook quinoa like pasta. Cook for 15 minutes in boiling water, strain and then add back to the hot pan for it to steam and get fluffy. this has been a game changer for me, perfect quinoa every time!

Layer it up: fluffy quinoa, mustard-y chicken, roasted veg and lots of sauce on top.

Whether you’re new here or have been around for a while, let me introduce you to a system that has been absolutely instrumental in eating a healthy diet, on a budget, in a way that is beyond delicious and doesn’t require hours of prep.

1) keep my pantry, fridge and freezer clean and organized and have either a mental and/or physical note of what I have stocked

2) assess the fridge, freezer and pantry

3) make a meal plan based on things I already have or what sounds good to make this week. I usually plan for 5-6 dinners, utilizing the leftovers from those dinners for lunches and 2-4 staple breakfasts (this is just what works for me and my fam of 4, everyone’s numbers are different)

4) make an exact list of everything I need

5) grocery shop. *try* to stick with only the things on my list. cough cough…cookie butter…cough…potato chips 😅

6) clean and store everything and spend 30-45 minutes making a healthful dinner each day so we eat up all the food I purchase!

My goal by the end of the week is to have a relatively “empty” fridge as we will have utilized all the bright, nutrient-dense food for energy for the week!

If you have any questions or comments hit me up in the comments! ☺️

Also, the reusable produce bags are linked under “lifestyle/every day” on my storefront (linked in bio) I love them!!

Tips for storing:

1) as a general rule, store fruit and veg at the temperature you found it at the store. For example, if it’s at room temp, keep it on the counter/pantry in your house. If it’s refrigerated, store in the fridge.

2) the major caveat to this though is avocados! I get asked literally all the time how my avocados are perfect. And it’s my strategy for buying and storing them. I buy them super green and hard and keep only one at a time (or more if I’m making guac or something) until it just perfect and then use it! The others I store in the fridge.

3) use the humidity controls on your crisper drawers! High humidity for most veg, low humidity for most fruits.

4) rinse and prep all your produce when you get home. Trust me, making dinner is so much less stressful when the lettuce is already washed and the cabbage is already shredded and the herbs are already rinsed!

5) wash your grapes and berries and keep them in the containers they came in! They are breathable and you can put in a little paper towel to absorb excess moisture!

What other tips and tricks do you like for cleaning and storage of produce?! 👇🏼

How I cook my rice!

You see me cooking rice on the stove a lot. And I’ve gotten a lot of questions on exactly how I do it- so here ya go! 🍚🍚🍚

The first thing you want to do, whether you’re cooking it in the rice cooker, on the stovetop or in an instant pot, is place rice in a fine mesh sieve and give it a really good rinse.

Rinsing the rice washes off the excess starch and helps the grains separate. It is crucial to help your rice cook up fluffy and perfect, not gelatinized and sticky. Rinse well until you see the water switch from cloudy to clear.

The commonly recommended water to rice ratio is 2:1. But I’ve found that a ratio of 1.75:1 works much better for fluffy, slightly drier rice.

Add the rice and water to a pot with a pinch of salt. Did you know? Adding a little bit of oil to rice can make your leftover rice lower in calories!? It must be cooled all the way down, but the added fat aids in converting the soluble starch into resistant starch which is not as readily digested by the body! 

Bring the rice to a boil, cover with a tight fitting lid, reduce the heat so the rice is just simmering for 10 minutes. After 10 minutes, turn off the heat, do not take the lid off or peak at all and leave for another 10 minutes. Then fluff the rice with a fork and enjoy! 

I served this with steamed veggies and orange chicken! I loosely followed the orange chicken recipe from the thestayathomechef.com if you want to look it up!

Let’s make it:

1 bunch asparagus, woody stems removed and cut into 2-3 inch pieces
2 small heads broccoli, chopped
1.25 cups Israeli couscous
1 can garbanzo beans, drained and rinsed
3 green onions, chopped
1/3 cup roasted pistachios, chopped
6oz block feta, crumbled
red pepper flakes and balsamic glaze, for serving 

Lemon vinaigrette:
-zest and juice of one full lemon
-1 tablespoon white wine vinegar
-1.5 teaspoons honey
-2 large cloves garlic, grated
-3/4 teaspoon each kosher salt and fresh cracked pepper
-6 tablespoons good quality extra virgin olive oil

Whisk together dressing ingredients until emulsified, set aside.

Blanch the broccoli and asparagus by boiling for 3 minutes and then adding immediately to ice water.

In the same water cook couscous according to package instructions.

Toss the couscous, garbanzo beans, veggies, green onions, pistachios with the lemon vinaigrette. Fold in the feta.

Top with crushed red pepper flakes and balsamic glaze.
