Question of the evening: what is your go-to “clean out the fridge” meal? 
 
Fried rice is totally mine.

It used to be frittata. Then for a while it was pasta. And now it’s fried rice.
 
It is THE thing I make when it’s the end of the week, I’m uninspired but gasp! I remember the bit of leftover rice in the fridge and the random veggies that didn’t get used up during the week.
 
Fried rice is:
·      Inexpensive
·      Easy
·      Quick
·      VERSATILE

I mean…you could toss nearly any veggie in fried rice and it would be bomb.

But when I made it this time I wanted to make like, REALLY good and extra flavorful so I decided to whisk up a little sauce to make it next level.

Enter: gochujang sauce.

Gochujang is a spicy paste used in Korean cooking made from red chili peppers, rice and salt and it’s deeply savory and absolutely delish. You can get it in either paste or sauce format (they are different!) and my recipe calls for gochujang sauce which is easier to find in just a regular grocery store than the paste (it’s in the Asian foods aisle!)

We whisk together 2 Tablespoons gochujang sauce, 2 Tablespoons soy sauce, 1 teaspoon toasted sesame oil and 2 teaspoons honey and this quick lil sauce REALLY bumps up the deliciousness factor 💯💯

You know what else I love about this recipe? How balanced it is! The ratio of veggies to rice is about 4:1 which means we’re getting in a ton of veg but still getting all the yummy fried rice vibes!

That’s why I don’t say foods are “bad” or off-limits, because there’s nearly always a way to make them part of a nutritious diet!

 I topped mine with a fried egg to keep things super quick and easy but you could add whatever protein you like!

This full recipe is on my blog! Link in my bio and story 😋🤩

Green curry:

Sauté some garlic, ginger and 3 tablespoons green curry paste in a swish of oil.

Add 2 cans coconut milk and bring to a simmer. Add one chopped sweet potato and simmer for about 15 minutes until softened.

Meanwhile press the water out of a cube of organic tofu, give it a chop and pan fry it for a few minutes each side until it is beautifully golden and crispy.

Add a whole bunch of kale and cilantro (or whatever veggies you have on hand) to the curry. Spoon over steamed rice or quinoa, top with a handful of fresh herbs, sprinkle of peanuts and some crunchy onions because why not.

This is nutritious and delicious at its finest!

Do you know those meals that you put on your plan for the week and it’s a random Tuesday and you’re going about your work day just SO excited that you get to make that meal for dinner tonight?
 
Yeah. That’s this meal.
 
It’s flavorful. It’s balanced. You eat it and it just makes you feel good.
 
And guess what? Do a little bit of work the day/night before to slice and marinate the meat and the next day dinner will be done in a SNAP.
 
Okay let’s talk about the beautiful balance here:
 
🥩Protein: about 25% of our meal is made up of beef- a wildly good source of protein, monounsaturated fats, iron and B vitamins. Protein helps us stay fuller for longer and helps us build and maintain muscle mass.

🍚Carbohydrate: another 25% of this meal is carbohydrate (rice!) Carbohydrate foods are quick sources of energy for our brain and bodies and are also very satisfying.

🥒Veggies: 50% of our meal is a wide colorful variety of nutrient-dense non-starchy vegetables which provide antioxidants, vitamins and minerals. These micronutrients fight against chronic disease and help our bodies function well.
 
And what makes it taste good?
 
Uhhhh. Where do I begin. Mostly it’s the AMAZING marinade on the beef that makes the thin strips of meat so tender and juicy and bursting with savory sweet flavor. Bulgogi is a Korean term that means “fire meat” and we are transforming our grilled meat into a wholesome meal (more reminiscent of bibimbap!) by adding loads of veggies and some fluffy steamed rice.
 
Trust me, you really need this one on your meal plan.

Okay all I can say is, you all need these sandwiches for your next brunch, lunch, dinner, breakfast, midnight snack!? Oomph. So yummy.
 
I love the balance of these sandwiches! The lean protein (chicken), heart-healthy fats (avocado), nutritious veg (red onion and lettuce) and 12g of whole grains and 4g fiber thanks to @daveskillerbread buns! The 21 Whole Grains and Seeds variety is hearty but also light and super satisfying.
Definitely worth putting on your grocery list for your next brunch or cookout!
#ad
 
Here’s how to make:
 
Caesar dressing:
¼ cup good quality mayo
1 tsp Dijon mustard
1 tsp Worcestershire sauce
1 tablespoon extra virgin olive oil
½ tsp anchovy paste
Juice of ½ lemon
¼ tsp each salt and pepper
2 garlic cloves
¼ cup finely grated parmesan cheese
 
Chicken:
2 chicken breast, butterflied (aka sliced in half lengthwise)
Salt and pepper
1 tablespoon extra virgin olive oil
1 tsp Dijon mustard
Juice of a whole small lemon
 
Everything else:
4 Dave’s Killer Bread 21 Whole Grains and Seeds organic burger buns + butter for toasting
10-12 butter lettuce leaves
¼ red onion, sliced
1 large avocado, sliced
6 slices bacon
Parmesan cheese, for grating
 
Whisk or blend together all of the Caesar dressing ingredients.
 
Slice the chicken breast lengthwise (this gives a nice thin piece that grills quickly without drying out). Season chicken with salt and pepper and add the olive oil, Dijon and lemon. Smoosh around and marinate 10 minutes or as long as you have time for!
 
Bake the bacon on a broiler pan or sheet pan for 25-30 minutes at 375, flipping the bacon at the 20 minute mark.
 
Spread a thin layer of butter on the buns. Grill the buns for about 3 minutes over medium heat until toasted. Grill the chicken for 3 minutes per side over medium high until internal temperature reaches 165.
 
Assemble! Toasted bun, Caesar dressing, lettuce, bacon, red onion, chicken, avocado, parmesan and more dressing. MUAH! It’s perfection.

I was vegetarian for 3 years in my early 20s.

My motivation behind that decision wasn’t for the environment or the animals or health.
 
It was to be skinny. and I thought you had to be vegetarian to be skinny. 🙄
 
I went about vegetarianism the COMPLETE WRONG WAY. My diet was devoid of fat, I was terrified of calories and there were about 10, maybe 20? foods on my safe list that I never deviated from. It was the unhealthiest time of my life.
 
Fast forward 10 years. Through my journey to becoming a registered dietitian and finding peace with my body and with food.
 
And something I learned is I LOVE eating vegetarian meals. Eating a plant-forward diet and prioritizing lots of plant-based meals is delicious, exciting and healthy!
 
I love tofu and quinoa and kale but I also love salmon and steak and cheese and there is room for ALL foods in a healthy diet.
 
I’ve shunned labeling my diet or my food choices and do not exclude foods or entire food groups unless I genuinely dislike them. Because I feel the unhealthiest when I’m restricting.
 
And NOW I know how to create balanced, nourishing and satisfying vegetarian meals like this kale power bowl.
 
It’s kinda like…how many superfoods can you pack into one bowl?
 
Dressing:
2/3 c @eatsantenuts chipotle almonds
1/3 c water
1/4 c extra virgin olive oil
juice of a lime
1 Tbsp nutritional yeast
1 Tbsp coconut aminos
Blend until super creamy.
 
Salad:
-purple kale, massaged with oil, lemon & salt
-sliced red onion tossed with white vinegar, pinch each of sugar & salt
-avocado
-1 block tofu + 1 Tbsp each arrowroot starch & cornmeal
-2 sweet potatoes
-spice mix: garlic powder, smoked paprika, onion powder, salt, pepper, nutritional yeast
-olive oil
-chipotle almonds
 
Press the water out of block of tofu. Pat dry and then tear/crumble it. Toss with the starch and cornmeal. Drizzle the tofu and sweet potatoes with oil and season liberally with your spice mix. Roast at 450 for 25-30 minutes until crispy.
 
Build your bowls, douse with dressing and add more crunchy almonds on top!

It is SO good. Nourished from the inside out!!

When I did outpatient counseling at a clinic, patients would come in ALL the time and say, “just tell me what I can eat and what I can’t eat.” 

My answer was always a resounding no, I will not be doing that.

Soooooo many folks looking to lose weight, manage their diabetes, improve their cholesterol, etc seek a quick fix. How can I fix this as fast as possible. A simple answer of exactly what to eliminate please.

And that’s why all the fad trendy diets DO have strict rules about all the things you have to eliminate and what foods are “ok” or “healthy.”

And if you are a person who can eliminate countless foods and even entire food groups for the rest of your life, I mean you do you boo.

But for the majority of the population these diets simply aren’t sustainable.

So then, what’s my advice? At the root, healing your relationship with food. Next, learning how to build balance in your meals and ADDING things like veggies and protein to make “fun foods” (like convenience noodles!) more balanced and satiating. Eating enough food, drinking enough hydrating fluids, moving your body in intentional heart pumping ways, these are all things that can gradually and sustainably lead you to better health.

So. Just a brief example of this in action for lunch today!! Package of @omsom soy garlic noodles and I ADDED several cups of fresh spinach, a big handful of green onions, a medium boiled egg (7 min simmering!) and a spoonful of chili crunch.

It was SO quick, easy and satisfying. I love that these actually come with ENOUGH SAUCE. Cuz I’m a saucy gal yum. (this product was gifted and so far I’m a huge fan!)

Also to drink-mango tea refresher!! Black tea, mango nectar, lemonade, lemon slices, YUM!

One time, I went to have a consultation with a trainer and “health coach” at the gym where I taught group exercise.

I didn’t tell him I was a registered dietitian and he literally didn’t even recognize me as one of the group fitness instructors 🙄 I was just really curious what he would say to me and what he would tell me to eat LOL.

And I mean, it went basically as you would expect. The most generic “4 sets of this, 4 sets of that” workout plan plus an even more generic 1600 calorie “meal plan”. The meal plan included meals like veggie egg cups and a protein smoothie for breakfast and “4oz white fish, 1 cup cooked quinoa and 2 cups vegetables” for dinner.

Now, there’s not anything necessarily “wrong” with what he told me to do. But I’m literally imagining myself as someone who doesn’t know much about food and nutrition, going home and baking a fish fillet, making some quinoa and steaming a bag of vegetables.

I eat it feeling virtuous that I’m following “the plan” but then because plain fish, quinoa and veggies is literally bland as it gets I end up feeling sad and deprived and craving a cheeseburger.

Has anyone else experienced this??

Because the piece of the puzzle we are missing here is learning how to actually implement healthy habits that are sustainable. That’s why I’m so passionate about showing HOW you can have a healthful diet that is actually fun and flavorful to eat.

So how bout we transform Chad Broseph’s ‘fish, quinoa and veggies’ into marinated and seasoned mahi mahi, steamed quinoa, bed of cabbage, Mexican street corn, avocado mango salsa and creamy chipotle sauce?

Because THAT is something I feel like eating :)

Fish marinade- lime, chili lime seasoning, garlic powder, smoked paprika, s&p, agave, olive oil. Wild caught mahi mahi fillets (from Costco!) broiled for 5-6 min!

Chipotle sauce- sour cream, chipotle in adobo sauce, water to thin a little bit

Mango salsa- mangos, avocado, cilantro, jalapeño, agave, s&p, olive oil

And first time trying the frozen Mexican street corn from Costco! Omg.

Three cheers to making the gym bro’s meal a delicious reality!! 🥭🥑🌶️🌽

Justice for cottage cheese!

I know lots of folks are very anti-cottage cheese, but I’m here for it.

It’s a fabulous source of calcium and has a whopping 14g protein per 1/2 cup!? 

I always recommend getting some quality protein in at snack time, so getting 15g+ at snack feels like a major win. Protein will help sustain you to your next meal and leave you feeling far more satiated than a meal/snack without.

Here’s the thing.

The reason convenience “junk” foods are so appealing and highly palatable is because they are high in sugar, sodium and fat.

And both “influencers” and commenters on social media looooove to rant about how evil foods are… table sugar, msg, salt, corn syrup, seed oils, the list goes on. They love to create fear around these foods and drum up more confusion and shame, instead of actually providing helpful, valuable content.

Because after all, fear and sensationalism get all the clicks and views.

No one wants to hear about nutrition from a registered dietitian who promotes balance and inclusion and empathy and cultural sensitivity.

ha…
😐🫠

Okay that got kinda dark, I digress. Sometimes how it feels on the internet though 😑

The POINT I’m trying to make. and here me out here… is to EMBRACE sugar, fat and sodium.

Because here’s the thing- we can harness the power of sugar, salt and fat to create healthful (YES HEALTHY), enjoyable, delicious meals.

By creating a sauce that includes salt (coconut aminos or soy sauce), sugar (brown sugar), spice (chili garlic sauce) and some fat (avocado oil) to stir-fry we are enhancing the flavor and enjoyment of chicken and vegetables- which would otherwise be pretty dang boring. I don’t know about you but I can only eat plain chicken, rice and veggies so long before I burnout hard.

It’s not about extremes. It’s about balance.

So let’s make some CASHEW CHICKEN. 

Sauce:
1/4 cup water
2 tsp cornstarch
4 Tbsp hoisin sauce
2 Tbsp coconut aminos
2 Tbsp white vinegar
1 Tbsp chili garlic sauce
2 Tbsp brown sugar

Whisk the cornstarch into the water. Then whisk in everything else.

Stir-fry
1lb organic chicken breast, cubed
lots of fresh garlic
lots of sliced bell peppers
green onions
cashews

Add a swish of avocado oil, brown up your chicken cubes. Add the peppers and stir-fry for several minutes. Add the garlic and sauce and cook a few minutes until thickened. Add the cashews and green onions and serve over rice.

SO GOOD!

Frittata:

1 tablespoon each butter and extra virgin olive oil
Big pinches of salt and pepper, ½ teaspoon brown sugar
8 eggs
1/3 cup half and half
Salt and pepper
6oz goat cheese, crumbled
Kale, spinach, any greens of choice!

Heat butter and olive oil over medium high heat in The Perco Pan. Add the sweet onions and toss to coat with the fat. Let cook, stirring every few minutes or so, for a total of about 30 minutes, until deeply caramelized. About halfway through, season with salt, pepper and sugar. Whisk together the eggs, half and half and 4oz of crumbled goat cheese. Season with s&p. When the onions are caramelized, add your nutritious greens, stir, reduce heat to medium low. Pour in the egg mixture. Crumble the rest of the goat cheese and green onions on top. Let sit for 4-5 minutes undisturbed, until edges are set. Transfer to the oven under the broiler for 3 min until golden brown on top.

This recipe is from @ambitiouskitchen! Called ‘best ever healthy banana bread’ on ambitiouskitchen.com but we errrr, took a few liberties lol.

3 very ripe bananas, mashed
2 eggs, at room temperature (very important to be at room temp)
1/3 cup pure maple syrup 
1/2 cup plain greek yogurt (whole milk or 2% is best)
1 teaspoon vanilla extract
1 3/4 cup whole wheat pastry flour
1 teaspoon baking soda
½ teaspoon cinnamon
¼ teaspoon salt
1/3 cup butter, melted and cooled
Optional add-ins: 1/2 cup mini choc chips, walnuts, coconut

Preheat oven to 350. Grease a loaf pan with butter or cooking spray. In a large bowl combine mashed bananas, maple syrup, eggs, yogurt and vanilla extract.

Add the flour, salt, baking soda and cinnamon and stir to combine. Melt the butter and fold it in. Don’t overmix! Next fold in any add-ins like mini chocolate chips, walnuts, coconut, etc.

Bake for 55-60 minutes. (mine took 64 minutes) Toothpick should come out clean. Let cool. Slice and serve! I ate mine with peanut butter and lil honey drizzle. SUPREME 🤩

One thing I want to start doing here is offering even MORE simple tips and tricks for eating healthy and cooking more.

Sometimes I hesitate sharing my “tips” because I’m like oh everyone knows that or everyone does that already, etc. what I’ve learned though is that there are actually quite a LOT of folks who don’t feel comfortable in the kitchen and don’t cook healthful meals on a regular basis.

So here we go, this is my very basic, but honestly life-changing, TIP OF THE DAY. ✔️🤓

Gather ALL of the ingredients for your meal and group them together on the counter before starting. Your protein, grain, veggies, spices, oil and vinegar. Get it all out. In one fell swoop. And put it on the counter. THEN start cooking.

You actually see me doing this at the beginning of every video 😉

And it may not seem like it, but this will truly expedite the amount of time it takes you to make a meal by like, 5-10 fold.

First is the obvious time saver of eliminating the 40 trips to the fridge, pantry, freezer, spice cabinet and baking cupboard.

and second, is the interruption in brain flow. When you’re in the middle of a task and have to leave to do something different, like get an ingredient from the fridge, it takes your brain more time to resume the task you were doing.

SO. If you don’t do this, I want you to at least try and then report back if it helps you find cooking/food prep a bit quicker and more enjoyable :)

And if you DO already do this, let me know in the comments!

When summer weather rolls around all I want to do is grab a baguette and scoop all things on top- marinated tomatoes, grilled dates, fig jam and brie, thinly sliced cukes and smoked salmon, feta and olives, I mean I could go on and on.

For the pickled strawberries I mostly followed @pinchofyum’s recipe:

-chopped strawberries
-1/3 cup rosé balsamic vinegar (she uses white balsamic vinegar which would work as well!)
-1/4 teaspoon salt
-1 tablespoon sugar
-1 tablespoon peppercorns
-water to fill the jar the rest of the way

Shake everything together and let “pickle” for 2 hours or up to 48 hours! These are probably best within the first few days so they won’t get soggy. I’m sure we will demolish the jar this evening.

Then I whipped up some goat cheese with a splash of heavy cream and spoonful of honey until it was spreadable. Fried some baguette slices in olive oil, shmeared on the goat cheese, piled on the pickled strawberries and crumbled on some fresh thyme.

30 grams protein.

That’s the optimal amount of protein in a meal to maximize muscle synthesis.

So, if you’re looking to build muscle and/or preserve lean muscle mass, first and foremost you’ll want to begin resistance training but also make sure you’re getting at least 30g protein in a meal at least once per day. If you can get 30g protein at multiple meals, great! But definitely do it at least once.

If you follow a typical “western” diet it’s possible that the majority of your protein intake happens at dinner. I would recommend that you consider upping your protein in the morning. Believe it or not, my highest protein meal is usually breakfast. This provides a foundation for balanced blood sugar and energy for my entire day.

This right here is an example of a 30g protein breakfast!

I’ve boosted my eggs with cottage cheese to 1) make them deliciously creamy and cheesy and 2) add 9g protein!

the breakdown of this meal is:
2oz sourdough bread
2 organic eggs
1/3 cup cottage cheese
1/2 small avocado
green onions
1 tablespoon crumbled feta
1/2 teaspoon chili crunch
bagel seasoning

453 calories, 40g carbohydrate, 23g fat, 31g protein, 4g fiber

(I will generally add a few handfuls of berries to boost the color and fiber as well!)

So, as we come off of the holiday weekend, I encourage you to continue fueling yourself and prioritize protein, fiber and water!

Here’s a vulnerable fact about me:

I get extremely triggered by extremes.

I’ve learned this about myself especially in the past few years when the world seems particularly…polarizing. 😭

If someone boasts a narrative that is extreme, one-sided, ‘this-is-the-only-way” type of ish... gives me the immediate ick.

Because 10 times out of 10 it is not that simple and it’s so important to practice respect, understanding and open-mindedness.

I have quite a few people who send me reels out of the blue that are very one-sided and pushing a particular agenda (why do people do this!?) and just a lil PSA, if you do that, I will immediately block you lol. 🙅🏻‍♀️

Nutrition and exercise extremes are very common offenders. There tend to be parties that are very extreme on “the best diet” or “this food is toxic” or “never ever eat this, it’s killing you” or “you should only ever exercise at X time of day” or “never pair x food with y food” or “eat this one thing to live longer” or “stop doing this exercise and start doing this one” etc etc.

And I have a secret to tell you.

All of that? 👆🏼

it’s BS.

Because guess what? every person’s body is uniquely different and will not respond to foods and exercise the exact same way as another person.

the best time of day to exercise?

is whatever time you will actually exercise.

“the best diet”?

is one that you can actually sustain.

SO.

Super simple: I made sugar cookies + cream cheese frosting + loads of berries on top

For the cookies:
2 3/4 cups all-purpose flour
2 teaspoons baking powder
3/4 teaspoon fine sea salt
2 sticks unsalted butter, at room temp
1¼ cups granulated sugar,
1 large egg plus 1 egg yolk
1 teaspoon vanilla extract
1/4 cup Greek yogurt (or sour cream)

Preheat the oven to 350°F. Line baking sheets with parchment paper. 
In a medium bowl, whisk together the flour, baking powder, and salt to combine. 
In a large bowl, use an electric mixer fitted with a paddle attachment on medium-high speed to beat the butter and sugar until light and fluffy, 2 to 3 minutes. Add the egg, egg yolk, and vanilla and Greek yogurt beat until combined. Slowly beat in the flour mixture.

Bake for 10-12 minutes. DO NOT OVERBAKE.

For the frosting:
1 stick butter
1 block cream cheese
3-4 cup powdered sugar
splash of vanilla

Beat it together until smooth and creamy!

We eat a lot of salmon in our house. It is a weekly staple. So I’m constantly on a mission to find new, delicious ways to enjoy it.

For the longest time, I was like what the heck is miso and where on earth do I find it? But miso is making a comeback! Or maybe it never went away… I’m just now discovering it’s deliciousness.

Miso is a paste made from fermented soybeans and usually a grain like barley or rice. It has a deep “umami” flavor that is iconic in Japanese cuisine. It adds a depth of flavor as well as the ability to thicken soups, sauces and gravies.

I find it at my normal grocery store in the international foods aisle! You can also find it at Asian food markets. 
In this recipe we combine it with butter, brown sugar, mirin, soy sauce and fresh garlic to make a glaze that is OMG so freaking good.

Plus mushrooms and snap peas are basically no chop veggies soooo… #winning.

This meal is so quick, easy, balanced and I am freaking telling you- DELISH.

And here I am again, making fried feta. Because it’s so freaking amazingly delicious and one of my favorite things to eat ever.

I make about a kajillion iterations of this exact meal…whatever veggies are in season, maybe orzo or wild rice or couscous, whatever herbs I have… but there’s always 1) creamy cashew sauce and 2) fried feta

I have the full, detailed recipe with lots of helpful tips and tricks on my website! (Link in bio) the version on my site is with roasted Brussels and sweet potatoes but this is the ‘summer’ version with tomatoes and zucchini!

Garlic cashew sauce:
1 cup roasted cashews, soaked in hot water for 30 minutes, drained and rinsed
1/4 cup cold water
Juice of 1/2 lemon
1 large garlic clove, grated

Blend together in a high powered blender until verrrry smooth.

The rest:
6oz block feta, cut into slices
2-3 tablespoons cornstarch
2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil 
1 cup orzo
2 zucchini, sliced into rounds
1 can garbanzo beans, drained and rinsed and patted dry
3 cloves garlic, sliced
1 teaspoon dried thyme
Fresh cracked pepper and kosher salt
Fresh mint, dill and basil (DON’T SKIP THESE!)
Grape tomatoes, sliced

Cook the orzo per package.
Dredge the feta slices in the cornstarch and shake off excess. Heat olive oil on medium high (nonstick works best here) Sauté for 2-3 minutes per side until golden brown. Remove to paper towel-lined plate. Add the garbanzos and sauté until golden and crispy, about 4-5 minutes. Add the zucchini and garlic and cook until just barely softened and caramelized (you don’t want the zucchini to be soggy!) it took me about 5 minutes. Season with salt, pepper and thyme.

Assemble! Spread cashew cream sauce on plate. Top with orzo, then zucchini and garbanzos, then feta. Garnish with tomatoes, TONS of the fresh herbs and a squeeze of lemon.

You’re welcome.

What is that one meal that you ate WAY too often when you were a college kid?

The “I’m broke and I don’t know how to cook” meal that you had on repeat over and over and over.

This is mine. 👆🏼 Well, and my other one was this weird AF quesadilla where I used egg whites instead of a tortilla and refried beans instead of cheese. RIP 💀🤡

But this was like my quintessential “college meal”. Of course back then it was made in the microwave instead of the air fryer and didn’t include any yummy spices or condiments or fresh herbs.

But to this day, when I’m single parenting, or don’t know what to make for lunch or dinner or am craving a “lazy meal”, I remember this oldie from the college days. 🍠

I nearly always have sweet potatoes on hand, black beans in the pantry, chicken sausage in the freezer, cheese and some type of green veggie in the fridge, so it’s something I can always rely on.

It is high in nutrients, high in fiber, high in volume and super tasty. 💯

It’s super simple:
1. Take a sweet potato and puncture it all over with a fork, drizzle with a touch of olive oil and season the outside with a little sea salt.
2. Air fry for 20 minutes at 400 degrees. Remove, slice in half and fluff up the insides. Season with what you like but I used Green Goddess seasoning and smoked paprika.
3. Add about 1/3ish cup black beans, 1 organic chicken sausage (I get the basil cracked pepper kind from costco!) and a sprinkle of sharp cheddar.
4. Grab a veggie (I like green beans, but you could do broccoli, cauliflower, bell peppers, zucchini, etc), spritz with avocado oil spray and season how you like. I used salt, pepper, garlic powder and green goddess.
5. Air fry the stuffed potato and green veggie for an additional 6-10 minutes (at 400) until it is cooked to your liking!
6. Top with green onions and hot sauce.

YUM!

This simple honey mustard glaze is wonderfully easy but packs a flavorful punch!

Combine:
1/4 cup-ish Dijon mustard
1/4 cup-ish honey
2 tablespoons mayo
Juice of 1/2 lemon
Taste and adjust if desired with more honey/Dijon/lemon to taste!

Butterfly two chicken breasts so that you have 4 thin pieces. Season with salt and pepper. Place in a bowl with half the marinade and let sit at least 3 hours, up to overnight.

Toss some broccoli with olive oil, salt, pepper and all purpose seasoning (I use 21 seasoning salute from Trader Joe’s)

Preheat grill to medium high and lightly brush grill grates with oil. Grill the chicken, 3-4 minutes per side, basting with additional marinade. Dump the broccoli on a grill mat or grill pan and cook, tossing occasionally, for about 12 minutes. Remove from grill and toss with freshly grated Parmesan and toasted almonds!

Serve with even more honey Dijon sauce, whatever starch/carb you like and any herbs you’re trying to use up!

Okay so my mother-in-law is a really good cook.

Honestly, between the first 21 years of his life with his mom making his meals and the past 11 years of my cooking, it really is not surprising that my husband does not know how to boil water. 😐🫠😂

 Here are the secrets to this marinade:

mayo: locks in moisture, provides fat and is the vehicle for all the amazing flavor in the spices, garlic and sweet chili sauce. (don’t worry, it doesn’t taste like mayo AT ALL)

Chinese five spice: this seems like a slightly weird spice to add since it has warming notes of anise and cinnamon but just trust. TRUST.

Sweet chili sauce: adds beautiful sweetness and balance

Fresh garlic: gets all sizzly and fragrant and perfect when you sauté up the shrimp!

Also note: the wild caught Argentinian shrimp from Trader Joe’s are THE best. Truly. I can think of no better word than succulent 🤌🏼😆

🍪BOURBON PECAN COOKIE SKILLET🍪

Just in time to make for your friends for your fourth of July cookout!

Trust me, there will not be a single crumb left.

Use code FLAVORFULLIFE for 15% off your entire order of Santé nuts- they have such fabulous flavors and what I love best is that they are candied, but just barely. Only 2-3g added sugar so they are a fun way to elevate salads, oatmeal, baked goods, anything you put them on.

A spinach salad with candied pecans or a bowl of oatmeal with candied walnuts feels just so… restaurant vibes, ya know what I mean?

Okay these cookies:
* 2 ½ cups all-purpose flour
* 2 teaspoons baking powder
* 1 teaspoon baking soda
* ½ teaspoon salt
* 1 cup unsalted butter
* 1 cup packed brown sugar
* ½ cup sugar
* 1 large egg
* 2 large egg yolks
* 3 teaspoons vanilla extract
* 1 cup @eatsantenuts bourbon pecans
* 8 ounces chocolate chunks
* 1/2 cup caramel M&Ms ❤️💙(optional, but fun!)
* flaky sea salt

(Recipe slightly modified from howsweeteats!)

Preheat the oven to 350 degrees F. 
In a bowl, whisk together the flour, baking powder, soda, and salt. 
Heat a 12-inch cast iron skillet over low heat. Let the skillet heat up for 5 minutes. Add the butter and let it melt completely, let it bubble and sizzle until it turns amber golden brown and has a few browned bits at the bottom. Stir in the sugars with a wooden spoon. Turn off the heat under the skillet.  Whisk together the egg and egg yolks in a bowl. Add it to the skillet sugar mixture and mix in right away with a spoon, quickly mixing so the eggs don’t cook from the heat. Stir in the vanilla extract. 
Stir in the dry ingredients until just combined. Add the pecans and chocolate. 
Make for 20 minutes if you like the gooey, underdone vibe and 25 minutes for more of a cookie bar. (Both ways are amaze) Top with flaky sea salt!

Pickled onions

On a slightly different note I want to share one of my all time favorite nutrition hacks-

adding non-starchy veggies to meals to:

1. increase the nutrient-density
2. stretch proteins to reduce cost
3. bump up the volume of the meal while keeping calories in check (aka bigger portion for fewer calories)
4. increase the fiber and satiation factor of the meal

By adding two large summer squash, 1/2 red onion and lots of garlic to our spaghetti sauce I am doing all four of those things!
(not to mention adding lots of flavor as well!)

What are everyone’s thoughts on this!? 👇🏼if you’re tempted by gimmicky fad diets for a quick fix, I challenge you to start with this simple strategy first! (ADD veggies!)

It’s a kajillion degrees out and I’m in a perpetual smoothie mood. ☀️🧉

But I have a confession. I’m pretty particular about smoothies. If I’m going to drink a smoothie
1) it has to be SMOOTH, like silky and creamy with no weird lumps 
2) I like her THICC. A thick creamy smoothie has way more staying power to me, than a thin one. I know I know, it’s the same ingredients it should have the same fullness factor either way right? Wrong. It’s science, just trust me. 
And 3) I want it to taste like it came from some bougie juice bar on the white sands of some paradise 🌴🥥🥭

I knowwww I always say “such and such” is like my favorite thing ever but…y’all this wildly basic mango protein smoothie…is my favorite smoothie ever. It is creamy and tropical, has only 4 ingredients and contains 35g protein!!

The key to a SMOOTH and THICC smoothie?! The blender.

A good, high-speed blender has the capability to blend at a low speed (which helps make a thicker smoothie) while also using high power (which makes a smoother smoothie).

My absolute top pick for a blender is the Vitamix Venturist v1200. I got it over 6 years ago and it is still my favorite kitchen investment. It has a large blending pitcher as well as a personal blender cup and I also purchased a small blender bowl which is handy for making smaller quantities of sauces or pesto or dressing. Right now you can get $100 off the Vitamix venturist when you use the link in my bio!! (Will also link in my story) if you’ve been dreaming of leveling up, now’s the time!!

And of course the first thing you should make is this mango smoothie:

🥭1 cup frozen mango chunks
🥭3/4 cup plain Greek yogurt
🥭1 scoop of your fave protein powder (check my bio for the link to the one I use!)
🥭1/2 cup 100% orange juice

That’s it! I also love to add several handfuls of spinach or kale and 1-2 tablespoons of hemp hearts and flaxseed.

Enjoyyyyy!

A dietitian’s monthly Costco haul comin’ in hot!

I will admit, I filmed this haul a week or so ago before my CSA started, otherwise I would NOT be buying cucumbers, tomatoes and mangoes as I am up to my ears in cukes, tomatoes and stone fruit! 🙃😂

But better late than never! This was a pretty big Costco haul for me, chock-full of my monthly staples. The items I buy so that I’m set up for success to create balanced, nourishing meals throughout the month.

When it comes to nutrition, I describe myself as having a whole foods diet. But me and diet culture may differ quite significantly in our definitions of whole foods.

For example, in my cart I have butter. and bacon. and potato chips. and bread. and pasta. Foods that don’t necessarily fit under your typical health halo.

But here’s the thing- to me, whole foods are ones that either are 1) just one thing or 2) a pretty simple combination of ingredients.

Bacon is just…bacon. And pasta is just… wheat, or chickpeas, or brown rice, etc.

So a salad that has crumbled bacon and cheese on it? whole foods. Pasta with butter and veggies? whole foods. Sandwich on bread with turkey and cheese? whole foods. And in my professional opinion, ALL amazing, healthy options.

It’s 2023 y’all, let’s stop fear mongering and creating shame or stigma around certain foods.

If you’re buying ingredients and turning them into meals that is one of the very very best things you can do for your health.

So whoever needs to hear this- stop getting hung up on this ingredient or that, and look at the  big picture. It’s about what you eat MOST of the time, and not about what you eat some of the time ;)

PRO TIP:

Have you all cooked/used chipotle peppers in adobo sauce? If you haven’t, HIGHLY recommend, they add such tremendous depth of flavor. Also, how many of you have used a WHOLE CAN of chipotle peppers when the recipe called for ONE chipotle pepper in adobo sauce?

Um. guilty. 🫣 and then my meal was un-eatable. lol. because these bad boys are spicaaayyyy. 🔥🔥

Okay also raise your hand if you used one chipotle pepper in adobo, stuck the can in your fridge and then it died a slow moldy death in your fridge and then you tossed the entire can?

Also guilty. 😭😭

So here’s my tip: keep your can of chipotle peppers in a small glass pyrex with a great sealing lid in the freezer. Then each time you need one, take it out, defrost for a few seconds in the microwave, grab the pepper you need and then pop it back in the freezer!

What do weeknights look like for you? As soon as I set foot in the kitchen I met with a chorus of demands for snacks, one toddler climbing on the counter, the other flinging pots and tupperware onto the floor. Trying to chop a few vegetables means I run the risk that the entire roll of toilet paper gets unspooled or the dog’s water bowl is upended and my 19-month old is drenched. 😵‍💫 It is a whirlwind of chaos that leaves me feeling like I’ve run a marathon when we finally sit down for our meal. 🫠
 
That’s why I NEED simple meal ideas. I used to be the type that loved the involved process of making pasta from scratch, nursing a risotto or slow-braising some meat. But now with littles, I just simply don’t have the capacity. 🙃 Pretty much everything I make is 30 minutes or less of prep that I nearly always get done while my girls are napping/having quite time. It alleviates so much stress during the 5pm hour. 🤪

This boursin tomato pasta is SO FREAKING EASY. It takes like 5 minutes to prep and 30 minutes in the oven and you’re done.
 I’m sure you remember when baked feta pasta took over TikTok and subsequently the internet back in 2020? 2021? I don’t remember. Well I hopped on that train and never looked back, I was smitten just like everyone else because duh, I love feta and I love tomatoes so how bad could that be? (said in my best Ina voice) 
And then I was thinking okay but how could I make this- but just a little different? A little cheesier, creamier and slightly more nutrient dense? Boursin cheese obviiii. Plus a few big handfuls of spinach! Yum.

You can of course add some additional protein like shredded chicken or italian sausage but I like to pair this with a huge green salad and call it good! I also love to use chickpea or lentil-based pasta for an added boost of plant-based protein and fiber.

You will find this recipe on my blog flavorfulife.com called “boursin tomato pasta” and the link is in my bio and in my story! Hope you try! 🍅

This weekend needs this sandwich ya know?? 🫱🏼‍🫲🏽

The TikTok grinder y’all.

No it’s not a dirty dance. It’s a sub sandwich. Apparently people call them grinders? Lol not in the Northwest but you guys can let me know where you’re from and what you call them LOL.

But basically… a creamy iceberg slaw with red onions and pepperoncinis, thinly sliced provolone toasted on a hoagie, piled with various meats like turkey and salami. 

Here’s how I made mine! There really are no “rules”, I think there are a lot of iterations!

Dressing:
-1 cup good quality mayo
-2 tablespoons red wine vinegar
-dried oregano
-red pepper flakes
-salt and pepper
-2 large cloves garlic, minced

Whisk together.

Slaw:
-iceberg lettuce
-thinly sliced red onion
-chopped pepperoncini
-big spoonful of the dressing

Toss together.

Sandwich:
-hoagie rolls
-thin sliced provolone
-various meats (whatever you like!) I used organic turkey, thin sliced ham, cappocola, soppressa salami, spicy coppa
-tomatoes (you should use a large tomato, sliced thick, but I forgotttt lol so I used cherry tomatoes)

Preheat oven to 400.

Toast the cheese on the bun for 5 minutes. Add the meats and toast for another 5 minutes. Pile on the slaw and tomatoes. Okkkkk. Yum factor 💯

Enjoyed with potato chips and kombucha. Picnic in the backyard!

Okay on a scale from 1-10 how would you rate yourself as a cook?

One big misconception I come across is that people think because I’m a registered dietitian that I’ve had some culinary training. Unfortunately, no. Dietitians are taught mostly the SCIENCE of nutrition and not really the practical application.

It’s funny, I literally had one cooking class in college and I remember one day our assignment was to make caramel and according to the recipe we had to heat it to this specific temperature and against our better judgement we just let it keep burning and burning because it wouldn’t reach the necessary temperature and when I tell you, it was BLACK. Literally black sugar in a pan. lol.

Good thing I’ve gotten better at making caramel 😉

Another thing people think is that I must’ve learned to cook from my mom or grew up in the kitchen. Which is also not true. Don’t get me wrong, I have ALWAYS loved to eat. But my mom’s cooking growing up was very… I don’t know the word… 90s? And she really did it herself. She never had me “make dinner” on my own.

And third misconception is that because I share food on the internet I must be a chef. When people say “you’re my favorite internet chef” I guess I’m flattered but I also roll on the floor because I feel like if Gordon Ramsay saw me cooking he’d put two pieces of bread on my ears and call me an idiot sandwich. LOL. 💀

SO. How did I learn to cook? 

The internet. The blogging boom of the 2010s. When all the now “big bloggers” were getting started. I was still in my late teens/early twenties at that time and certainly didn’t have the skill, knowledge or confidence to start my own food blog. BUT I do owe a ton of credit to Bon Appetit, Food and Nutrition magazine and @howsweeteats for teaching me how to cook.

And now here I am! A pretty decent cook. And even a cook confident enough to create my own recipes and share them with you all!

However lol, I took some creative liberties with this recipe but I cannot claim it as my own. It is from @halfbakedharvest called “sheet pan chili crisp beef rice bowls.” and it was uh.may.zing.

Anyway, would love to hear your thoughts in the comments!! 👩🏻‍🍳👇🏼

I was inspired to make these “salmon power bowls” from a restaurant menu I saw recently. I didn’t actually order it because it seemed like something I could EASILY make at home and I have a firm policy that on the very rare occasion I go out to eat I’m ordering something I don’t/can’t make at home!

How about y’all? Do you order things that are familiar or do you only order things you can’t make yourself??

This power bowl is SO easy:

-wild caught salmon, patted dry
-1/4 cup tamari or soy sauce
-1/4 cup honey
-ginger (optional)

-cucumbers tossed with rice vinegar, toasted sesame oil, pinch of salt, pinch of sugar, jalapeño lime crunch and sesame seeds

-edamame with toasted sesame oil and salt

-steamed rice

-crispy onions, green onions, sriracha and sesame seeds for garnish!!

Whisk together the tamari or soy sauce and honey. Add half to the salmon and roast at 450 for 10-12 minutes. Add the rest of the sauce when it comes out of the oven, it’ll thicken on the hot pan. Spoon extra on the salmon when you serve.

Layer rice, salmon, extra honey tamari sauce, edamame, cucumbers, crispy onions, green onions, sriracha and sesame seeds! 

YUM AND HAPPY FRIDAY 💃🏼💃🏼

Oomph. A summer panzanella salad is just soooo freaking GOOD.

I always cube up the heels of my sourdough bread from the week and keep them in the freezer that way whenever I want fresh croutons I can just drizzle with some olive oil and toast them in the oven (my full method and recipe for garlic butter coupons is included in my upcoming digital cookbook!)

For this salad you will need:
-about 2 cups stale sourdough cubes drizzled with olive oil, butter and garlic and baked at 350 for 14 minutes
-3 gorgeous heirloom tomatoes, chopped
-2 peppers, chopped 
-2 cucumbers, seeds scraped out and sliced into half moons
-fresh mozzarella cheese, chopped
-lots of fresh basil

Dressing:
-juice of two lemons
-2 teaspoons Dijon
-2 cloves garlic, grated (or 1 teaspoon garlic paste)
-2 teaspoons honey
-1/2 cup extra virgin olive oil
-salt and pepper

Stir together the salad (make sure to use a big enough bowl 🙃lol) and pour on the dressing, toss and let sit for 20-30 minutes so all the flavors can meld, YUM.

For a LOT of years people have told me that I need to write a cookbook. In fact, I also see cookbook requests in other food creators’ comments sections all the time.

But here’s the thing. Just because someone likes food or is good at cooking does not mean they should write a cookbook. 😬🤷🏻‍♀️

Recipe development is an art and a science and something that really does take a lot of time and practice.

For years, I was truly truly not ready to “write a cookbook.” I was simply learning how to cook, how to fall in love with food and flavor, how to make food I wanted to eat.

And now, finally, I have the confidence and skills to create my own recipes! Which is what I’ve been working on for the past 6 months or so. In my small pockets of time here or there I’ve been recipe testing, taking pictures and creating a compilation of really yummy recipes that I truly love. My cookbook ebook is coming out in just under a month, right in time for back to school and the craziness of the fall season. 

It is over 45 recipes designed into easy to follow weekly meal plans accompanied by recommended prep steps and grocery lists and I personally cannot wait to use it and cook through the whole thing with y’all! Here’s how I made mine!

1 large eggplant, cubed
6 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil, divided
1 large summer squash (or zucchini), cubed
1 medium yellow onion, finely chopped
2 sweet bell peppers, large dice
5 large cloves garlic, chopped
5 large heirloom tomatoes, chopped with their juices
2 tablespoon tomato paste
1 teaspoon dried thyme
1 teaspoon Italian seasoning
¾ teaspoon sugar
1 teaspoon kosher salt, divided
chopped fresh basil

Heat 3 tablespoons of oil in a large nonstick pan over medium heat. Add the eggplant and season with a pinch of salt. Cook, stirring frequently, until soft and starting to brown, 10 to 12 minutes. Transfer to a plate and set aside.

Add another tablespoon of oil to the pan and add the squash/zucchini and cook, stirring frequently, until tender-crisp, 3 to 4 minutes. Season with a pinch of salt and set aside.

Add two more tablespoons of oil to the pan and add the onion and bell pepper. Cook, stirring frequently, for about 5 minutes. Add the garlic and continue cooking for about 3 minutes more. Add the italian seasoning, thyme, sugar and 1/2 teaspoon salt. Add tomato paste and the tomatoes/tomato juices. Cook, stirring occasionally, until the tomatoes are broken down into a sauce, 8 to 10 minutes. Add the cooked eggplant to the pan; bring to a gentle boil, then reduce the heat to low, and simmer, uncovered, for about 10 minutes or until the eggplant is soft. Add the zucchini and cook for 1 to 2 minutes more, then taste and season with more salt and pepper, if needed. Sprinkle with fresh basil and serve warm with GARLIC BREAD.

The garlic bread is a combo of butter, mayo, parmesan, garlic on ciabatta bread and for the exact recipe you will need to get on the waitlist for ebook. (link in bio!)

In a medium sauce pan combine:

1 1/2 cups apple cider vinegar
1/2 cup water
1 teaspoon kosher salt
1 tablespoon sugar

Over medium heat whisk until dissolved, remove from heat.

2 red onions, thinly sliced
several peeled garlic cloves and pinch of black peppercorns (optional)

Place the onions in a jar or glass container. Pour the brine over top. Seal. Store in fridge for up to 4 weeks!

Super easy baked pesto pasta! 🍅🍃

1lb pasta, cooked per package instructions
3/4 cup pesto
1/2 cup starchy pesto water
1 cup grated provolone, mozzarella or Italian cheese blend
1lb cherry or grape tomatoes

Toss pasta, pesto, water, grated cheese and tomatoes together in a baking dish. Season with salt, pepper and red pepper flakes. Top with fresh mozzarella. Bake for 20-25 minutes at 400 degrees until cheese is melted.

dressing
-1/4 cup tahini

-1 teaspoon pure maple syrup

My diet used to be super repetitive. When I was in my early 20s ALL I cared about was eating as few calories as  possible so only certain foods were “safe”. I ate a lot of oatmeal, egg whites, veggie burger on a sandwich thin. In hindsight, my diet was not healthy at all. It was just low calorie. And I was miserable. Like physically miserable all.the.time. Stomach aches galore. I figured that that’s just what skinny people had to endure in order to be skinny?

But I finally was so so tired of feeling sick that I just started eating again. Not in a healthy way, more in a binge-y kind of way. And I gained a lot of weight. And my stomachaches and fatigue and feeling terrible all the time got better, but didn’t go away.

And I did my masters in nutrition and became a dietitian and finally started understanding how to eat in a truly healthful way. Eating a VARIETY. Eating ENOUGH. Eating BALANCED. And could you believe it? When I started eating enough of the right things I naturally lost weight AND felt so much better.

Because eating the double fiber english muffin with 1 teaspoon of peanut butter for years on end because it was the only thing I deemed “safe” didn’t seem like a great option. When our diets are that strict there is so much glorious nutrition that we miss out on.

So anyway, all of that to say that now I focus on being strong, not skinny and healthy, not hungry. I eat meals that are vibrant, focused around vegetables and fruits but also include protein and whole grains.

Like this random girl dinner that totally hit the spot:
-2 organic basil and cracked pepper chicken sausages, sautéed in a touch of olive oil
-1 delicata squash seasoned with olive oil, salt, pepper and a touch of maple syrup, roasted at 425 for 20 minutes and then broiled for 1 minute (lots of delicata coming in my CSA!)
-steamed organic brown rice
-tons of fresh spinach
-a quick vinaigrette with 1 tablespoon olive oil, 1 tablespoon apple cider vinegar, 1/2 teaspoon dijon and 1/2 teaspoon honey
-sprinkle of goat cheese

Simple, balanced and something to give me ENERGY to thrive.

Happy girl dinner! 💃🏼

Listen, I know I’ve got some kale haters out there. Common complaints include too bitter, too chewy and an overall tough pill to swallow. Literally. But here’s the thing- kale is a nutrient powerhouse. One 100g serving of kale provides 35 calories, 3 grams protein, 4 grams fiber and an abundance of phytonutrients like Vitamin C, Vitamin A, Vitamin K, Calcium and Iron. 🤩‼️
 
Kale also provides a variety of tremendously helpful antioxidants (like quercetin and kaempferol) which protect against chronic disease, support heart health, slow the growth of cancer cells and ease inflammation.
 
And widely considered the runner-up for the most nutrient-dense dark leafy green vegetable? Spinach, of course.
 
So what I’m trying to say here is Kale AND Spinach salad? = health, my friends.
 
Some vegetables need just a little more love than others to make them taste amazing, so that’s what we’re going to do.
 
Tips for making kale taste great:
•   Slice it thin. I like to remove the leaves from the ribs, stack them on top of each other and use a sharp chef’s knife to thinly slice the kale leaves into ribbons.
•   Give it a massage. We all feel better after a massage, right? Rubbing the kale with a touch of oil and lemon juice breaks down the fibrous texture making it less chewy, less bitter and more palatable.
•   Dress it up. Gone are the days I would avoid salad dressing for fear of the calories or fat. A simple dressing made with balsamic vinegar and extra virgin olive oil not only provides amazing flavor but increases nutrient absorption. I am particularly fond of this fig balsamic dressing.

You will find both the salad and dressing recipes on my website flavorfulife.com! Simply follow the link in my bio!

Be still by taco loving heart!

Korean-inspired beef tacos with kimchi slaw featuring crunchy, flavorful, good for your gut @clevelandkitchen classic kimchi. 🤩🤤

I love the depth of flavor the kimchi adds to the slaw and if you’re looking for yummy ways to incorporate more probiotics into your diet, kimchi is a stellar way to do it.
 
Probiotics are live active cultures, or good bacteria, that populate our gut and play innumerable roles in our bodies including bolstering our immune system, preventing chronic diseases, aiding weight maintenance, promoting regular bowel movements and beyond. Kimchi is one of my favorite probiotic-rich foods to consume on a regular basis to promote a healthy gut microbiome and I encourage you to do the same. 💯
 
With these tacos duhhh.
 
Beef
1 ¼ lb ground beef
1 T avocado oil
¼ cup coconut aminos or soy sauce
3 T brown sugar or honey
2 t toasted sesame oil
1 t sriracha
3 cloves garlic, minced or grated
1 inch knob ginger, finely grated
 
Kimchi Slaw
1 ½ cups green cabbage, finely shredded
½ cup @clevelandkitchen classic kimchi, roughly chopped
½ cup julienned carrots
½ bunch cilantro, roughly chopped
4 green onions, chopped
½ lime, juiced
Splash of toasted sesame oil
Pinch of salt
 
Sriracha Mayo
5 tablespoons good quality mayo
1-2 teaspoons sriracha
½ lime, juiced
Water if desired, for a thinner consistency
 
Assembly
6-inch flour tortillas
1 avocado, thinly sliced
Crushed peanuts
Lime slices
Sesame seeds
 
Whisk together the coconut aminos or soy sauce, brown sugar, sesame oil and sriracha. In a large skillet heat the oil over medium-high heat, add the ground beef, using a spatula to break it up into small pieces. Brown the beef until completely cooked through. Reduce heat to medium-low and add the garlic and ginger, stir-frying for 60 seconds until fragrant. Add the sauce and toss to combine.
 
Toss together slaw and whisk up the sriracha lime mayo.
 
Layer the tortillas with garlic ginger beef, kimchi slaw, avocado, peanuts, a big squeeze of lime, more fresh herbs, all the things!
 
You can find Cleveland Kitchen Kimchi at your local Kroger!

On Saturdays I always sit down and plan out dinners for the week ahead. Then I make a list of everything I need to execute those meals and go grocery shopping. I like to stick with one grocery trip per week because with two toddlers, making constant trips to the grocery store is a special kind of torture.

One time I saw this meme that said “how does it feel to decide what your family eats for three meals a day, seven days a week, for at least the next 18 years?”

And I just really resonated with that because yes. I am she. She is me. I decide what everyone in my household eats all day. every day. (I am quite sure this is many of you as well)

When I plan out my meal ideas/recipes for the week I look for a few things:

1) does it look and sound absolutely delicious?

2) is it balanced with protein, satisfying carbs and LOTS of non-starchy vegetables?

3) does it take less than 30-45 minutes to prepare?

I have good news my friends, these beef teriyaki bowls fit the criteria PERFECTLY. They are quick, easy, flavorful, balanced and something my whole family devours. Well, Penelope loved everything, Lia (my elder toddler) was slightly more skeptical but toddlers be toddlers amirite?

And want to know the true test of a good recipe? Whether or not you are stoked for the leftovers. And when I tell you, I am SO EXCITED for lunch.

Saucy beef and veggies piled high on a steamy rice pillow and finished off with a drizzle of tangy kimchi mayo, MUAH! Dinner time perfection.

As a food creator my fridge and pantry can get out of hand sometimes.😵‍💫😵‍💫

I cook and develop so many recipes that my fridge feels bursting at the seams! And you all know, I’m very food waste averse and I’m not always able to do this, but I like to use up everything I have BEFORE getting more.

So this is one of those meals where I was like okay here is this random stuff I need to use up, what the heck do I make.

Roasted sheet pan meal for the win!

Basically take any and all veggies you need to use up, chop ‘em and throw in the oven! I used carrots, potatoes, sweet potatoes and cabbage, tossed with olive oil, salt, pepper and the 21 seasoning salute from Trader Joe’s! Roasted at 450 for 30 minutes.

Halfway through cook time I added some chicken sausages- I love the organic paleo cracked pepper and basil chicken sausages from Costco.

And of course sauce. Super quick and easy creamy cashew sauce!

2/3 cup cashews, soaked in hot water for about 15 minutes, then drained
1/3 cup cold water
2 cloves garlic
1/2 teaspoon each salt and pepper
Juice of 1/2 lemon
2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil

Blend everything until super smooth and creamy- it is SO GOOD.

I’m SO happy to be partnering with USA Pulses to bring more awareness to what pulses are and how wildly beneficial they are! 
 
I am and will always be an advocate for more pulses in our daily diet. I like to aim for ½ cup a day of beans, lentils, chickpeas or chickpea-based foods like hummus, falafel or veggie burgers. Pulses are an invaluable source of fiber, plant-based protein, folate, potassium, iron, magnesium and B vitamins.
 
If you are also interested in increasing your intake of nutrient-dense pulses, this recipe is a delicious way to do so! 🤤🤤
 
Chickpea walnut taco filling:
1 can chickpeas, drained, rinsed and patted dry
1 ½ cups walnuts
1 chipotle pepper in adobo sauce + 1 tablespoon adobo sauce
1 clove garlic
½ teaspoon salt
1 teaspoon cumin
½ teaspoon smoked paprika
1 teaspoon chili powder
2 tablespoon olive oil
1 lime, juiced
 
Creamy cilantro sauce:
1 cup cilantro
½ lime, juiced
Pinches of salt and pepper
½ teaspoon cumin
2 tablespoon hot and sweet pickled jalapenos + 1 tablespoon jalapeno juice
¼ cup mayo
1/3 cup plain Greek yogurt
 
Assembly:
Warmed tortillas
Shredded cabbage
Avocado slices
Hot and sweet pickled jalapenos
Pickled red onion
 
Filling:
Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Pulse together filling ingredients except for the lime juice (five 1-second pulses in your food processor). Spread on a lined baking sheet and roast for 20-23 minutes until fragrant and deepened in color. Squeeze on the juice of a whole lime and toss.
 
Sauce:
Blend together and season to taste with salt and pepper. Toss several big spoonfuls with finely shredded cabbage.
 
Assembly:
In warmed tortillas layer in slaw, chickpea filling, more sauce, avocado, onions and jalapeno.
 
DIVE IN. These are so good.

Give me this meal all day every day. kale, quinoa, squash, feta, garlic, extra virgin olive oil, THESE are true, comforting foods that I absolutely crave.

How to make:

Roast: 2 small sliced Delicata squash tossed with EVOO, s&p at 425 for 22-25 min until tender and browned.

Whisk together: 1 clove grated garlic, 1 teaspoon pure maple syrup, 1 teaspoon Dijon mustard, 2 tablespoons apple cider vinegar, 1/4 cup extra virgin olive oil, salt and pepper to taste

Slice: block feta into planks, coat with a sprinkle of cornstarch. Sauté in extra virgin olive oil on high heat for just a minute or so per side. (If you cook too long the feta will melt completely and be a mess!)

Assemble: toss baby kale and cooked grain of choice (I took a shortcut with a steamable pack of organic quinoa and brown rice) with vinaigrette. Top with roasted squash, thinly sliced apple, fried feta and honey roasted pistachios. Drizzle with extra dressing.

This. THIS is what healthy eating means to me. And why I am so not a fan of the cookie cutter meal plans or 1200 calorie guidelines that you get from the latest internet diet or Chad Broseph, your resident gym bro.

Because while those might “work” for a brief time they actually don’t work at all. Because I have worked with a lotttttt of people and never once have I met someone able to actually maintain those type of regimens.

What works for me is focusing on whole foods, cooked from scratch, without restriction/worrying about macros this or calories that. I crave and want to eat GOOD STUFF, veggies, fruits, greens, whole grains, etc.

So anyway, this is once again my plea/reminder to staaahp making nutrition so complicated! Tune out the diet culture noise and find the nutrient-dense foods that help you thrive ☺️

Caramelized onion Brie chicken 🥹🤤

I’ve been making this meal for years and it is one of my absolute faves. It’s SUCH an easy way to turn boring, bland chicken breast into a stellar dinner.

A few notes:

Caramelized onions- I have one word. Patience. People pull their onions waaaay too soon. These are not burnt. They are beautifully caramelized. I add a touch of balsamic vinegar, salt and brown sugar to aid the caramelization!

Brie- slice off the rind but don’t be too precious about it. It’s fine if there’s a little bit on there.

Chicken- I like to slice my chicken breast in half lengthwise so it’s thin, cooks really quickly and stays moist and yummy!

Sides- go wild! I’m in a delicata era rn. 💁🏻‍♀️ I seasoned my veggies super simply- olive oil, salt, pepper and 21 seasoning salute!

Need a dinner that doubles as a simple weeknight win AND an impressive dinner party menu
item?

I got you. I’m so excited to be partnering with @go_raw to create some deliciousness with their
Organic Sprouted Pumpkin Seeds.

We eat pumpkin seeds year-round in my house and they are just truly a nutrition powerhouse.
EIGHT grams of protein in just ¼ cup!? Like what? 🤯

Not to mention a variety of important
antioxidants, phytonutrients and minerals.
My girls eat these pumpkin seeds every morning in their oatmeal but I also love to use them in
savory preparations like this pumpkin seed crusted salmon.

Salmon slathered with a glorious cilantro lime pumpkin seed pesto and topped with pumpkin
seed breadcrumbs for amazing crunch and texture.

Here’s how you make it!

Cilantro lime pesto:
1/3 cup Go Raw Organic Sprouted Pumpkin Seeds
1 cup fresh cilantro
2 cloves garlic
½ lime, juice of
½ t kosher salt
½ t fresh cracked pepper
1 t agave
½ cup extra virgin olive oil

Topping:
¼ cup Go Raw Organic Sprouted Pumpkin Seeds
¼ cup panko breadcrumbs
½ t kosher salt
½ t fresh cracked pepper
3 T butter, melted

Assembly:
1lb wild caught salmon
Roasted veggies or salad or grain of choice

Preheat oven to 450 degrees.
Pesto:
In a food processor, pulse together the pumpkin seeds, cilantro, garlic, salt and pepper. Add the
olive oil, agave and lime juice and process until smooth and creamy.

Topping:
In a food processor, pulse the pumpkin seeds, breadcrumbs, salt and pepper. Add the melted
butter and process again to evenly moisten the crumbs.

Pat the salmon dry with a paper towel. Season with just a touch of salt and pepper. Slather
each piece of salmon with 2-3 tablespoons of pesto.

Add 2-3 tablespoons breadcrumbs,
pressing them down to adhere to the pesto.
Roast for 8-10 minutes until salmon is just cooked through, it doesn’t take long!

Serve with your favorite veggies and salad topped with MORE pumpkin seeds, pom
arils, feta, pesto and drizzle of olive oil!

I hope y’all grab a bag of Go Raw Organic Sprouted Pumpkin Seeds so you can whip up this
delicious salmon ASAP!

I don’t really make spaghetti the same way twice but here’s how I made this one:

1 spaghetti squash, cut in half, insides scooped out
olive oil, salt and pepper

Season inside of spaghetti squash with olive oil, salt and pepper and place face down on a lined baking tray, add about 1/2 cup water. Roast at 400 degrees for 25-28 minutes, don’t overcook! 

1lb lean organic ground beef
1 tablespoon olive oil
1 sweet onion, chopped
6 cloves garlic, minced
1/4 teaspoon each kosher salt, fresh cracked pepper and red pepper flakes
1-ish teaspoon each: onion salt (from TJs), Italian seasoning, dried basil, dried oregano
1/4 cup tomato paste
1/2 cup red wine (totally optional, I only used it bc I had it)
1 24oz jar marinara sauce

Brown the beef and remove to a paper towel lined plate. Add olive oil and sauté the onion until softened. Add garlic, seasonings, tomato paste and sauté another few minutes. Deglaze the pan with red wine and let it sizzle out. Return beef to the pan and add marinara sauce, let simmer for 20 minutes until deepened in flavor.

Serve over spaghetti squash or regular spaghetti with parmesan, pepper and basil! 🍝🍝🍝

Florida Grapefruit season BAYBAY!! I need two hands in the air from all my grapefruit lovers! #Ad

I live in a city that is COLD and DARK all winter long. So, what do I do? Eat as much sunny Florida Citrus
as possible, obvi. Grapefruit is one of my true wintertime faves- there is not a winter fruit that
competes with a perfectly ripe, juicy, naturally sweet and tart Florida Grapefruit.

I’m excited to be partnering with @floridagrapefruitus to tell you all about its versatility and nutrient
density!

When it comes to bang for your nutrition buck, it doesn’t get more effective than grapefruit.
Grapefruit contains an abundance of phytonutrients-aka the plant compounds that protect against a
variety of chronic illnesses. It has water and fiber, is low in calories and includes important minerals like
potassium.

I love eating Florida Grapefruit straight up but my goodness, I WILL be making this grapefruit shrimp
ceviche all winter long. It was the perfect light and refreshing dinner and it took me somewhere not dark
and freezing cold lol.

Here’s what you need:

1/3 cup fresh squeezed Florida Grapefruit Juice (1 whole grapefruit)
1 Florida Grapefruit, peeled, segmented and chopped
1/3 cup fresh lime juice
1lb wild caught Argentinian shrimp (raw, peeled and deveined)
1 cucumber, chopped
1 jalapeño, minced
½ red onion, minced
½ bunch cilantro, chopped
½ teaspoon each kosher salt and fresh cracked pepper
For serving: fried corn tortillas, avocado, olive oil, flaky sea salt

Add shrimp to a pot of boiling water and cook for 1 minute, until just cooked through. Place shrimp in an
ice bath to stop cooking process. Roughly chop the shrimp into pieces and add to a large bowl.

Submerge the shrimp in the fresh squeezed Florida Grapefruit and lime juices and marinate 20
minutes. Add the remaining ingredients, toss to combine and season additionally with salt if needed.
Serve straight up or on tostadas with smashed avocado!

season.

I’m not even a Rice Krispie treat gal.

I make my ultimate chocolate peanut butter Rice Krispie treats once a year for camping but otherwise there are about a million other things I’d rather have as a treat.

I saw Lindsay of @pinchofyum make these salted caramel Rice Krispie bars I was like yeaaahhhh imma need those.

Here’s the thing I think is key with me and Rice Krispie treats. I don’t want like an airy, sticky “light” Rice Krispie treat. I want a dense, chewy, buttery, soft bar with depth of flavor beyond marshmallow sweetness.

And that is EXACTLY what these are. Super compact texture (make sure to really presssss them into the pan), salty, caramelly and amazing.

All recipe credit to @pinchofyum, they are on her site called “salted caramel Rice Krispie bars”!

1 cup unsalted butter
1 cup lightly packed light brown sugar
1/2 cup heavy whipping cream
2 teaspoons flaky sea salt
10-ounce package miniature marshmallows (I used 16 ounces for extra gooey!)
12-ounce box of Rice Krispies or crispy rice cereal

Melt butter in a large pot over medium heat.
Add sugar and whipping cream; stir to incorporate. It will take a minute, but as it heats, you’ll start to see a smooth, creamy caramel mixture form. Heat over medium-low heat for 5-7 minutes, until you have a slightly thickened caramel sauce that coats the back of a spoon.
Remove from heat and stir in the salt. Taste and adjust for more salt if you want.
Add the marshmallows and stir until melted.
Stir in the cereal. Press mixture into a 9×13 pan. I like to like the pan with parchment with overhang on each side so I can easily pull them out of the pan to slice into bars.
Cool slightly, cut into squares, and enjoy! Serve at room temp or from the refrigerator!

Alright first order of business: pans.

Second order of business: creamy tomato pasta.

Here’s how to make it:
1lb mild Italian sausage (not traditional, but I added for some more protein!)
2 T extra virgin olive oil
1 shallot, minced
5 cloves garlic, minced
¼ cup tomato paste
3 T vodka
½ t each kosher salt and fresh cracked pepper
Pinch of red pepper flakes
1 cup heavy cream
½ cup freshly grated parmesan cheese
1 T butter
8oz orecchiette pasta (or your favorite cut of pasta)
1 cup starchy pasta water

Brown the sausage until fully cooked. Remove to a paper towel-lined plate and wipe out any grease. Add olive oil and sauté shallot and garlic until softened, about 5 minutes. Add tomato paste, and red pepper flakes and cook until deepened in color, 2-3 minutes. Add the vodka and let it sizzle out. Add heavy cream, parmesan and butter, stirring to combine.

Cook pasta per the package. Do NOT forget to reserve at least 1 cup starchy pasta water before draining.

Add sausage and pasta to the sauce along with pasta water. Toss to combine. Top with 
basil, parm and pepper.

This is one that will WOW your dinner guests with very little effort on your end- 10/10 recommend.

I was uninspired to make dinner this week but I know that home-cooked meals with a variety of veggies, protein and balance will help me stay my best, most productive self. So here we are 💁🏻‍♀️ with this AMAZINGLY delicious and comforting tortellini bolognese.

I used to view marinara-based pasta and pesto-based pasta dishes as too entirely separate things but I’m here to offer this wee little PSA- pesto IN your marinara sauce is SO good and adds an extra irresistible layer of flavor. Plus a splash of cream because why the heck not.

1 tablespoon olive oil
3/4lb lean organic ground beef
3/4lb italian sausage
2 shallots, minced
1 red bell pepper, chopped
4 stalks celery, finely chopped
8 cloves garlic, minced
pinch red pepper flakes
1/2 teaspoon each salt and pepper
1/2 tablespoon each dried oregano, dried basil, Italian seasoning
3 tablespoons tomato paste
2 24oz jars good-quality marinara sauce
1/3 cup pesto
1/4 cup heavy cream
2/3 cup freshly grated parmesan
1 24oz package three cheese tortellini
fresh basil

Brown up the beef and sausage in a large skillet, then remove to a paper towel lined plate. Add a swish of oil and sauté the shallots, bell pepper and celery until softened, about five minutes. Add the garlic, seasonings and tomato paste and sauté until fragrant, 2 minutes. Return meat to the pan, add marinara sauce, pesto, cream and parmesan. Boil tortellini according to package instructions and then fold the pasta into the sauce. Top with parmesan, black pepper and fresh basil!

I served this with a heaping pile of arugula with some of my homemade caesar dressing (the recipe for my caesar dressing is both in my cookbook and on my blog flavorfulife.com!)

Chocolate peppermint whoopie pies ARE YA KIDDING ME RN?!?

Who wants one?! 🙋🏻‍♀️

Recipe is ever so slightly adapted from twopeasandtheirpod.com! (Called ‘peppermint chocolate whoopie pies’)

For the whoopie pies:
	•	2 cups all-purpose flour
	•	1/2 cup cocoa powder
	•	1 teaspoon baking soda
	•	3/4 teaspoon salt
	•	1/2 cup unsalted butter, at room temperature
	•	1 cup packed brown sugar
	•	1 large egg, at room temperature
	•	1 teaspoon vanilla extract
	•	1 cup buttermilk, at room temperature
For the peppermint filling:
	•	3/4 cup unsalted butter, at room temperature
	•	1 1/4 cups confectioners’ sugar, sifted
	•	1 teaspoon vanilla extract
	•	1/2 teaspoon peppermint extract
	•	1/8 teaspoon salt
	•	2 1/2 cups marshmallow crème 
	•	Candy cane kisses, chopped

Instructions
Preheat oven to 350 degrees F. Line large baking sheets with parchment paper or silicone baking mats.

In a medium bowl, whisk together the flour, cocoa powder, baking soda, and salt.

Using a stand mixer, beat the butter and brown sugar together until light and fluffy, about 2 minutes. Add the egg and vanilla extract and mix until combined.

With the mixer on low, add 1/3 of the flour mixture, half of the buttermilk, 1/3 of the flour, the rest of the buttermilk, and finally the remaining flour mixture. Mix until just combined.

Use a small cookie scoop to scoop about 2 teaspoons of batter onto the prepared baking sheets, placing the whoopie pies about 2-inchres apart.

Bake for 10 minutes or until the whoopie pie centers spring back when gently touched. Let whoopie pies cool on the baking sheets for 5 minutes and then transfer to a cooling rack.

Using a stand mixer, beat the butter and sugar together on medium speed until light and fluffy, about 2 minutes. Beat in the vanilla extract, peppermint extract, and salt. Add the marshmallow crème and mix until combined. Refrigerate the filling for 30 minutes.

To assemble the whoopie pies, spread the mint filling on flat sides of half of whoopie pies and top with remaining pies.

Roll the cookies in the chopped kisses.

LOTS of requests for the sugar cookie dough recipe I used for my peppermint sugar cookie cups that I shared earlier this week!

I make a BIG batch of this dough and then use half for cookie cups and half for these sprinkle cookies. This recipe makes 6 dozen cookies (A LOT) so feel free to half the recipe for a smaller batch!  1 cup butter, softened 4oz cream cheese, softened  3 cups sugar
4 eggs 2 Teaspoon vanilla extract 2 Teaspoon almond extract 5 Cups flour 4 Teaspoons corn starch 2 Teaspoon baking soda 1/2 Teaspoon salt 1 cup-ish NONPAREILS 😂 sprinkles

* In bowl of stand mixer fitted with paddle attachment, or a large bowl using hand mixer, cream together the butter, cream cheese, sugar, eggs, and extracts until light and fluffy. About 5 minutes.
* Scrape down the sides of the bowl with a spatula. Add the flour, corn starch, baking soda, and salt. Mix together on low/medium speed for one minute, until combined.
* Refrigerate dough for two hours before baking.
* When dough is done chilling, preheat oven to 350 degrees. Line two baking sheets with parchment paper, or spray with non-stick cooking spray.
* Pour the sprinkles into a medium bowl, and roll tablespoon sized balls of dough into the sprinkles.
* Place the cookies onto prepared baking sheet, spacing 2 inches apart.
* Bake for 9 minutes. These should not turn golden brown, and will still look wet when they come out of the oven. 
* Allow cookies to cool on baking sheet for 3-5 minutes before moving to a wire rack to cool completely.

(Recipe adapted from thesaltymarshmallow.com!)

6 tablespoons butter
1 cup peanut butter
2 cups powdered sugar
Splash of vanilla
Pinch of sea salt

Classic peanut butter blossoms!!

A cookie always on my cookie list :) so simple and so good!

1 cup granulated sugar
1 cup packed brown sugar
1 cup creamy peanut butter
1 cup butter, softened
2 eggs
3 cups all-purpose flour
1 1/2 teaspoons baking soda
1 teaspoon baking powder
Additional granulated sugar (about 2 tablespoons)

Heat oven to 375°F. In large bowl, beat 1 cup granulated sugar, the brown sugar, peanut butter, butter and eggs with electric mixer on medium speed, or mix with spoon. Stir in flour, baking soda and baking powder.

Shape dough into 1-inch balls; roll in additional granulated sugar. Place about 2 inches apart on ungreased cookie sheet.

Bake 8 to 10 minutes or until edges are light brown. Immediately press 1 chocolate candy in center of each cookie. Remove from cookie sheet to wire rack.

It’s official. I’m on a bread bender.

I WILL be making this 4 ingredient loaf every week for the foreseeable future.

It’s soooo easy, flour, yeast, salt and water….are ya kidding me? And it makes an absolutely incredible loaf of fresh baked bread.

I prep this after the girls go to bed the evening before I know we will need it, let it proof for a good 18 hours or so and then plop it in the oven at dinner time and BOOM. Bread magic.

3 cups flour
1/2 teaspoon active dry yeast
1 1/2 teaspoon salt
1 1/2 cups room temp water

Stir together the flour, yeast and salt. Add the water and stir until a dough ball forms, it’ll look kinda scrappy and weird. Cover with plastic wrap and a clean kitchen towel and let it sit at room temp for 12-18 hours. I made mine at about 11pm and it was perfect for dinner the next day! Store in a draft free area.

Remove, shape into a dough ball. Preheat oven to 450 and place a 6 quart Dutch oven in the oven to preheat. When oven is preheated place dough on a piece of parchment paper and put it in the Dutch oven. Cover and cook for 30 minutes, remove the lid and cook an additional 10-15 minutes until browned and beautiful.

You will need a Dutch oven or an oven safe pot with a tight fitting lid to make this recipe. A Dutch oven is my absolute number one favorite pot/pan in my kitchen, I use it for everything!

For anyone who wants to start the new year wasting less, saving more and eating more flavorful food!! 

So much better than storebought AND you get to be resourceful with veggie scraps that might otherwise be doomed for the trash.

I eat a lotttt of vegetables and whenever I have peels, parts, scraps that aren’t edible I place them in a large gallon Ziploc and keep it in the freezer. Over the course of several weeks I easily fill the bag to the brim with veggie pieces that would be great in broth. Then I bust out the stockpot!

Simply add your veggie scraps, fill with cool water and add any other aromatics like ginger, thyme, bay leaves, black peppercorns and a tablespoon or so of kosher salt. Bring to a simmer and reduce by about half, this will take 4-5 hours.

Strain your broth into glass jars and keep in the fridge for a couple weeks or in the freezer for a couple months. (If freezing, store in a Ziploc and lay in flat!)

You could of course also add some chicken bones/carcass.

And then after capitalizing on all that flavor and nutrition you compost the scraps! We started composting a few years ago and will never go back.

This is such a fabulous and easy way to get more use out of your wonderfully nutritious veggies, reduce waste, save money, it’s just all around winning.

You’ll want to of course make sure all of your produce is cleaned REALLY well (even things like onion that have a peel) and prioritizing organic when you can is also helpful!

Here are veggies that work fabulously for broth:
-onions, leeks, green onions, shallots, garlic
-potato and sweet potato peels
-carrot, parsnip, rutabaga peels
-stems from parsley, kale, cilantro, thyme, rosemary, any fresh herb!
-celery greens
-zucchini and summer squash, winter squash
-green bean trimmings
-bell pepper 
-pea pods
-mushroom stems

Veggies to avoid throwing in there would be broccoli, Brussels sprouts and cauliflower (these will lend a really bitter taste) and jalapeño or spicy peppers (if you don’t want it to be spicy)

Okay friends, I challenge you! Start making a veggie scraps bag in your freezer today!! 😁 who’s in?! 👇🏼🥕🥒🥬🫑🧄🧅🥔

Are you a meal prepper!?!

I get asked alllll the time what I do for meal prep. And my answer is “I don’t.” 😅

I do meal PLAN, but I consider that a bit different than meal prep.

In my brain, meal prep means five straight hours on a Sunday afternoon making 4-5 servings of the same breakfast, lunch and dinner to have all week. 

Meal plan means picking the dinners for each day of the week, maybe chopping some veggies, prepping a sauce or two ahead of time and then making dinner each evening.

We can debate in the comments whether you believe my definitions to be valid. 😆

And there’s no wrong way of course, this is simply what I do.

The real moral of the story here is that these honey harissa chicken bowls need to be on either 1) your meal plan or 2) part of your meal prep 😂💯

Seriously, this bowl comes together with beautifully balanced Mediterranean flavors and it is just SO GOOD. The honey harissa chicken especially my goshhh, this is not your average chicken dinner friends!

* 1/2 teaspoon each kosher salt and fresh cracked pepper
