The whole San Marzano tomatoes are KEY here. Please don’t mess around with any other type. A 28oz can is a wee bit on the expensive side at the grocery story but you can get a 3 pack for $9.99 at Costco so fer SURE grab those during your next run!

Also something I learned while writing this post: It is technically spelled Arrabbiata, with a double “b”, but apparently Americans just chronically spell it wrong so when you google a recipe, ‘arrabiata’ is the preferred spelling… so anyway yeah… one b or two, it’s delicious and you should try it. 🤤🔥

ABC Juice! #ad 

Bursting with antioxidants, vitamins and minerals. Featuring the nutrition powerhouse- beets!

I love using my @cuisinart Juice Extractor to make quick, easy, wholesome juices. It’s so easy to use, quick to clean and I loooove a beautiful, homemade veggie and fruit juice!

For the longest time I’ve disliked beets. But as a dietitian I TOTALLY nerd out on their powerful nutrition potential. Beets can help lower blood pressure, improve blood flow, increase oxygen utilization and improve athletic performance and reduce inflammation in the body.

And paired with other epically nutritious foods like carrots, ginger, lemon and apple? So many reasons to make this ABC juice. 
#cuisinart_partner 

The best part? This @cuisinart juicer is on sale for $30 off until January 14th via #linkinbio !!

Here’s how to make it. In the Cuisinart Juice Extractor combine:  
-4 beets  
-4 carrots  
-2-3 apples  
-4-inch knob ginger  
-2 lemons  
Pour yourself a glass over ice right away and then store the rest in an airtight container or small juice shot bottles!

Then, of COURSE we have to use that beautiful rainbow pulp so muffins it is.

In a large bowl whisk together:  
-1 heaping cup juice pulp  
-1 cup unsweetened applesauce  
-½ cup pure maple syrup  
-2 eggs  
-⅓ cup melted coconut oil  
-1 teaspoon vanilla

Then fold in:  
-1 ½ cup white whole grain flour  
-1 ½ teaspoon baking powder  
-½ teaspoon baking soda  
-½ teaspoon salt  
-1 teaspoon cinnamon 

Preheat the oven to 425 degrees. Scoop the batter into a lined or greased muffin tin (the batter looks a little sus, trust the process) and bake for 5 minutes. Without opening the oven, reduce the temperature to 350 degrees and bake for another 20 minutes, or until a toothpick entered comes out clean.

Coconut cashew curry noodles with chicken and veggies!

Y’all want to know my TMI scenario?? I’ll tell you.

It’s wildly ironic that I ended this voiceover with “you won’t regret this” because as it happens, I really really did regret this lol.

I made this for dinner just a couple nights ago and unfortunately it all came back up as I was blessed with the stomach bug that is making its nasty rounds.

Seriously, I would rather be ANY kind of sick than stomach sick. I will take the most ratchet cold, influenza, covid, give me whatever over stomach flu. Seriously, I think I get wrecked harder than the average girl 😭

Y’all can vote in the comments what kind of sickness you think is the worst 🥴😂

BUT. I promise promise promise it had nothing to do with this recipe because in fact, it IS delicious.

Here’s how to make it:

Blend together your sauce:
1 cup raw or roasted cashews
1 can coconut cream (or coconut milk)
1 cup water
1 tablespoon toasted sesame oil
2 tablespoons seasoned rice vinegar
3 tablespoons red curry paste
2 tablespoons brown sugar or maple syrup
2 tablespoons coconut aminos (or soy sauce)
2 inch knob ginger, freshly grated
2 cloves garlic, minced

Stir-fry:
honestly whatever type of protein and whatever veggies you like!

I did chicken breast seasoned with salt and pepper, 1 small head broccoli, 1 red bell pepper and 2 carrots, sliced into coins.

Stir-fry the chicken for 5-7 minutes in a swish of avocado oil until browned and cooked through, remove to a bowl.

Add the veggies and stir-fry another 5-7 minutes until crisp tender, don’t overcook!

Cook noodles according to package instructions, I use the millet and brown rice ramen noodles from @lotusfoods.

Add the chicken and noodles to the veggies, and douse everything with sauce.

This actually makes quite a lot of sauce and I had a little leftover but you could use it all if you wish.

Top with green onions, cashews and sesame seeds.

You *probably* won’t regret this. 😉😭

20 minute pesto chicken sausage gnocchi skillet!

May not be the most beautiful thing I’ve ever made but TRUST, my friends, trust. It’s delish.

I have an indoor hydroponic garden and literally cannot keep up with the amount of basil I have constantly so first order of business, quick homemade pesto! (so much better than store-bought 😉) Recipe for my super basic pesto recipe is on my blog! (I’ll link it in my bio and story)

THEN this recipe is kind of a “measure with your heart” type of scenario but here’s the gist:

1 small sweet onion, chopped
2 large cloves garlic, sliced
4 chicken sausages, sliced (I get the paleo basil ones from Costco)
1/2 teaspoon each red pepper flakes, salt and pepper
1 lb package gnocchi
1/2 cup pesto
3/4 cup-ish starchy pasta water
1 cup freshly grated parmesan
2 tablespoons heavy cream
whatever veggies you love! (I steamed some broccoli in the microwave🙃💁🏻‍♀️)

Sauté the onion, garlic and chicken sausages in a swish of olive oil over medium heat in a cast iron skillet until slightly browned, softened and fragrant.

Cook gnocchi per the package instructions, when it floats to the top transfer the gnocchi to the skillet. Save some pasta water!

Add 1/2 cup pesto, 1/2-3/4 cup of the pasta water, parmesan and cream and stir. Adjust with an extra splash of pasta water, as needed, until your desired consistency is reached. The sauce should be slightly thickened and coat the sausage and gnocchi. Serve it up with some veggies and dinner is DONE.

There are three things I would eat for dinner from my college cafeteria:

1. the salad bar with spring mix, raw veggies, garbanzo beans and straight vinegar as the dressing
2. plain white rice and the steamed broccoli/cauliflower/carrot mix. That’s it.
3. a veggie burger on a whole wheat sandwich thin with lettuce and mustard

This is what I was convinced health had to look like. No spices, dressings, sauces, oil, etc.

I was vegetarian at the time and I still love vegetarian meals but they’ve got to look like THIS chimichurri bowl, not my sad, sad meals of the past.

Like be fr Erica. STRAIGHT VINEGAR!? 💀

I share openly about this now because my recovery and journey is what led me to be the registered dietitian and food fanatic that I am today!

I’ve said it once and I’ll say it a million more times, nutrition is not black and white or one size fits all. I’ve found what works for me and I have truly never been healthier or happier. I make food choices that fuel my active lifestyle and that are genuinely DELICIOUS.

Ultimately you do what works for you! I’ll just be over here trying to provide some nutrient-dense inspo, ya feel me? 🤤

The recipe for these chimichurri bowls is on the blog (link in bio and story!) and I cannot wait for you to try.

And so I don’t feel so exposed, y’all can drop your cringiest “diet meal” in the comments. 😬

Normalize making burgers with literally whatever you have on hand 🙃🍔

This meal was borne from leftover chimichurri. Ya know, the chimichurri bowls from yesterday? So we take the leftover chimichurri, stir it into some mayo and voila, chimichurri aioli ✨

I used organic ground beef seasoned with garlic paste, one-ish teaspoon each salt, pepper and smoked paprika and some dashes of Worcestershire sauce.

Smashed into patties, baked at 475 degrees for 5-6 minutes per side. After you flip, add whatever cheese you love, I had sharp cheddar.

I served these on @daveskillerbread whole grain buns with some arugula and pickled red onions. Don’t come for me for the arugula on a burger, I LIKE IT OK 💀 Plus it’s what I had. And then some sweet potato fries on the side 🍠😏

So the moral of this story is…you use what you have. This was a super yummy dinner! Not every evening has to be the most beautiful, elaborate meal 😉
